# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university-of-cambridge
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The **2010 United Kingdom student protests** were a series of demonstrations in November and December 2010 that took place in several areas of the country, with the focal point of protests being in central London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Largely student-led, the protests were held in opposition to planned spending cuts to further education and an increase of the cap on tuition fees by the Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition government following their review into higher education funding in England.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Student groups said that the intended cuts to education were excessive, would damage higher education, give students higher debts, and broke campaign promises made by politicians.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The first major demonstration occurred on 10 November, jointly organised by the National Union of Students (NUS) and the University and College Union (UCU).
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] It involved between 30,000 and 50,000 demonstrators marching through central London, with several hundred branching off to attack and occupy the Conservative Party headquarters.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] This measure brought condemnation from the establishment and a divide within the student movement over the appropriateness of such tactics.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The National Campaign Against Fees and Cuts (NCAFC) called for a mass walk-out and demonstration on 24 November, with occupations taking place at campuses throughout the UK.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A march in central London was kettled in Whitehall, resulting in violent confrontation with protesters.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Further demonstrations were held in central London on 30 November, when police clashed with protesters and kettled them in Trafalgar Square, while other protests took place throughout the country.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Another central London protest took place on 9 December, the day that the proposed reforms were passed into law, with protesters clashing with police and being kettled in Parliament Square.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The student protests were unsuccessful in their aim of preventing the government's reforms in England.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] However, in Wales and Northern Ireland, devolved authorities decided not to increase the fees, which led to differing fee levels for the devolved nations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The demonstrations were highly controversial in the UK, being condemned for instances of violence and vandalism by both the establishment and by protestors.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The behaviour of the Metropolitan Police in dealing with the protests was also widely criticised for alleged instances of untruthfulness and excessive use of force.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In November 2009, the Labour Party government of Prime Minister Gordon Brown commissioned a study into higher education funding in England.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Chaired by Lord Browne of Madingley, the former chief executive of BP, the report was to be titled the Browne Review.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In the build up to the 2010 general election, the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Nick Clegg, pledged that he would vote against any proposed increase in tuition fees if elected to Parliament.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Following the election and resulting hung parliament, Clegg made an agreement with the Conservative Party to form a coalition government in which Conservative leader David Cameron became Prime Minister and Clegg became Deputy Prime Minister.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Browne Review was subsequently published in October 2010, and contained the suggestion that the government should remove outright the existing cap of £3,290 on tuition fees.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The government rejected this proposal, instead choosing to keep a cap but increasing it to £9,000.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] David Willetts, the Minister of State for Universities and Science, stated that the measures were "a very progressive package" and "at the end of this we will have a better university system than we have at the moment".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Contravening his pre-election pledge, Clegg expressed support for the rise in the cap on tuition fees, which would result in future students paying higher fees for their university education.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Student union leaders were critical of the cuts.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The National Union of Students (NUS) feared that the increased cap on tuition fees would prevent potential students from poorer backgrounds from attending university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many protesters focused in particular on Clegg's campaign promise that he would oppose any rise in tuition fees.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Two weeks before, on 28 October, a protest was held in the University of Oxford to coincide with a visit from the Liberal Democrat minister and Business Secretary Vince Cable.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Cable cancelled his visit after taking advice from the police about the protest.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several days later, on 3 November, there was a student protest in Dublin.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The subsequent London protest was described by one Irish reporter as "scenes bizarrely similar" to those in the Irish capital.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The initial event was the largest student protest in Britain since the Labour government first proposed the Teaching and Higher Education Act in 1998.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The first major demonstration in protest at the government's proposed reforms was held on 10 November 2010 in central London, jointly organised by the National Union of Students (NUS) and the University and College Union (UCU).
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] This demonstration was officially known as "Fund Our Future: Stop Education Cuts", although also termed "Demo 2010" or "Demo-lition 10.11.10".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Arriving from all regions of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, approximately 30,000 to 52,000 protesters attended the demonstration.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Political groups that sent contingents to take part included the Labour Party, Plaid Cymru, the Green Party, Socialist Workers Party, Socialist Party, Revolution, Young Communist League, Revolutionary Communist Group, and Communist Students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A few members of parliament (MPs) joined the demonstration, among them Labour MP John McDonnell, who told reporters: "This is the biggest workers' and students' demonstration in decades.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] It just shows what can be done when people get angry.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Representatives of the National Pensioners Convention also took part, with the group's banner carrier, Janet Shapiro, stating that: "We're here because we believe education should be free, funded by the taxpayer.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Hunt stated that making the public university system in Britain "the most expensive in the world" was unfair, that discouraging young people from going to college was not progressive, and that the increase in tuition fees represented further debts for students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The rally was also addressed by NUS President Aaron Porter and the Trades Union Congress Deputy general secretary Frances O'Grady.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] O'Grady offered the message to the government that: "Don't you dare tell us we're all in this together.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The deficit certainly wasn't caused by the students." The protest was scheduled to end at 2 pm, but slightly overran.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police were expecting 20,000 demonstrators to turn out, well below the 50,000 figure most widely quoted in the press after the event, and did not expect any violence, so deployed only 225 officers to police the event.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In the afternoon, as protesters passed the Houses of Parliament and moved towards Tate Britain for the rally, several thousand surrounded 30 Millbank in Westminster, campaign headquarters of the Conservative Party, despite attempts by NUS organisers to stop them.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Forcing their way past the limited police presence, approximately 200 people broke in and occupied the building, whilst a thousand more cheered and supported them from outside.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] These protesters lit placards on fire, and smashed windows before occupying and vandalising the reception area.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Staff working in the building were evacuated by police around 1 pm.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Around 100 protesters proceeded to the roof of the building, chanting slogans including "Greece!
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Initial press sources blamed this action on a group of anarchists.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] This was later disputed, with a reporter from *The Guardian* noting that most of the protesters occupying the building were students who had been radicalised in opposition to the cuts, and were not all political anarchists.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Riot police from the Territorial Support Group arrived an hour after the building was occupied to remove the protesters.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In retaliation, the police were pelted with eggs, rotten fruit, banners, and shards of glass.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] One of the protesters on the building's roof, Edward Woolard, threw a fire extinguisher onto the police below.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] He received instant criticism from some of the protesting crowds, who called on those on the roof to "stop throwing shit".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] To control the situation, police used the controversial technique of kettling to trap the protesters within Millbank Square, the forecourt to 30 Millbank, whilst protesters on the outside of the building were pushed back.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The police began letting demonstrators out of the building from 6:30 pm, arresting those whom they believed were responsible for vandalism.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In all, 14 people were injured and required hospitalisation, at least three of whom were police officers, whilst police arrested 35 of the demonstrators, sending them off to various police stations around the city.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Later accounts that the numbers arrested had risen to 54, (33 men and 21 women), ten of whom were aged under 18 and the majority of whom were students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The actions of a minority, out of 50,000 people, is regrettable." Oxford University's Student Union (OUSU) President David Barclay issued a statement declaring that "OUSU supports the rights of students to protest non-violently.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Contrastingly, other student leaders, trade unionists, and academics expressed support for elements of the occupation of 30 Millbank.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Meanwhile, various university Conservative societies around London condemned the protests, and criticised students' unions for providing the "false impression that the majority of students are left-wing" and opposed to the governments' proposed reforms.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police Service admitted that they were unprepared to deal with the occupation of 30 Millbank, something which they had not been expecting.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Sir Paul Stephenson, the Metropolitan Police's Commissioner, told the press that he was "embarrassed" by how police had lost control of the situation, and condemned what he saw as "thuggish, loutish behaviour by criminals".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Stephenson remarked that "the one thing I would say is that it must have been an awful time for the people trying to go about their daily business in those buildings.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] I feel terribly sorry that they have had to go through what must have been quite a traumatic experience...
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] We are determined to make sure that sort of thing does not happen again on our streets.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] I'm clear on that, the Met is clear on that." His views were echoed by Mayor of London Boris Johnson, who stated: "This is intolerable and all those involved will be pursued and they will face the full force of the law...
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police commissioner has assured me that there will be a vigorous post-incident investigation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Prime Minister David Cameron condemned the occupation of Millbank, stating that he would not abandon his position on the issue of education cuts.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Speaking from the 2010 G20 Seoul summit in South Korea, Cameron said the occasion had been "extremely serious" and praised the "bravery" of the police officers.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] He also stated that the actions of the protesters were "unacceptable" and that "I was worried for the safety of the people in the building because I know people who work there".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The following morning, Clegg went on ITV's *Daybreak* to state: "I should have been more careful perhaps in signing that pledge [to not increase tuition fees]...
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the time [prior to his election] I really thought we could do it.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The *Financial Times* reported that an anonymous vice-chancellor from a London university had told them that the violence would undermine the campaign, and that it "could not have gone better for the government.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In the following days, smaller protests were held in Manchester and Cambridge, with no violent confrontations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 11 November, student protesters occupied a building at the University of Manchester for three hours, demanding to see the accounts that discussed how government funding cuts would affect students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Between 60 and 100 students held a peaceful sit-in at Manchester's John Owens Building on Oxford Road after an NUS meeting earlier that day.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Representing this group, protester Jeremy Buck said: "This is just what a few students who had the energy left after the London demo managed to achieve...
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Imagine what will happen when they have enough time to organise properly for the 24th.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] It is a matter of watch this space." That same day, protesters at the University of Cambridge held a demonstration against the cuts at the university's annual science, engineering and technology careers fair.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 23 November, anti-education cuts protesters had assembled outside of the offices of *The Guardian* newspaper, where Clegg was giving his Hugo Young lecture.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They brought out an effigy of Clegg, sentencing it to death and executing it by hanging, shouting the slogan "Nick Clegg, shame on you, shame on you for turning blue".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A second significant demonstration took place in London on 24 November, which again led to clashes with police, this time outside Whitehall, after police kettled a large crowd.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] An organisation known as the National Campaign Against Fees and Cuts (NCAFC) organised a mass national walk-out of education and protest for 24 November.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] As a part of this, demonstrations were held in London and other locations across the United Kingdom.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The NCAFC encouraged protesters to use social media to invite others to join them.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several thousand protesters, most of whom were students or school children, gathered in Trafalgar Square, central London, late in the morning.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They proceeded toward Whitehall shouting the slogan, "fuck David Cameron".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Believing that there had been a lack of officers at 10 November demonstration, the Metropolitan Police drafted in 1000 police officers from across Greater London to oversee the event, almost five times the number at 10 November.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police informed press that they planned to monitor fringe elements within the demonstration whom they believed planned to encourage "vandalism and violence".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At Whitehall, just before 1 pm, police prevented the protesters from reaching Parliament Square and the Houses of Parliament, setting up a line of riot police to kettle the protesters.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A reporter *The Guardian* described the crowd at this point as being "predominantly good natured, although very noisy".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Nonetheless, the demonstrators tried to push through the police line, leading to clashes.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] An unoccupied police van which had been left in the midst of the crowd was vandalised; protesters rocked it back and forth, climbed on its roof, smashed its windows, wrote graffiti on it and threw a smoke bomb inside.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A group of school girls encircled the van, urging people not to vandalise it.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At around 6 pm, mounted police charged at the north end of the crowd to push them back; despite video evidence police denied that this was an actual charge, describing it as crowd control using horses.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Various bus shelters and ticket machines in the area were vandalised, with Transport for London diverting buses away from the unrest.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Approximately 200 protesters were unable to escape and remained kettled in Whitehall.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police falsely informed press that the crowd were provided with toilet facilities and water; protesters disputed these claims on social media, with ULU President Clare Solomon commenting on Facebook: "we're still illegally kettled in the freezing cold on Whitehall.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] No food, water or toilets despite what the police are telling the media.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Thousands of young people needing to go home." To keep warm, protesters set fire to a ticket machine within the Square, prompting riot police to secure the machine and put out the flames.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] From 9 to 10 pm, police permitted the rest of the Whitehall protesters to leave, approximately nine to ten hours after they had first been contained, some being searched as they left.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] During the clashes, police arrested 41 protesters.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Across the UK, protesters occupied university buildings in at least 12 universities.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 23 November, protesters occupied the picture gallery corridor of Royal Holloway, University of London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They were later joined by supportive members of university staff who took part in what was labelled a "teach-in".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 24 November, the Language Centre at London South Bank University was occupied for 51 hours by over 100 students as part of the "Defend LSBU!
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They're quoting Harry Potter rather than Che Guevara." Protesters also occupied the University of East London, demanding that university managers "put pressure on the government on the issue of H[higher] E[ducation] cuts and tuition fee rises".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A group of about 100 occupied a lecture theatre in the Roscoe Building.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the University of Oxford, students initially occupied the Radcliffe Camera.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the University of Cambridge, 200 students scaled the fence of Senate House and marched onto the grounds of King's College, then on 26 November students started an 11-day occupation of part of Old Schools, the main administrative block of the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the University of Bristol, 2000 protesters clashed with police when they tried to move into the city centre.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In Brighton, 3000 demonstrators marched through the city, with nearly 50 occupying a university building.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Hundreds of students from Kingston University and various local schools staged an impromptu march through the town and a sit down protest at College Roundabout, leading to one arrest.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Hundreds of them had walked out of the local Allerton Grange High School to join the demonstration, and later occupied the Michael Sadler lecture theatre and a room at Leeds Metropolitan University.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A room at the University of Plymouth was also occupied.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At Cardiff University, around 200 protesters occupied a lecture theatre after failing to gain entry to the vice-chancellor's building.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] During the Whitehall incident, the Metropolitan Police publicly defended their use of kettling, with Chief Inspector Jane Connors claiming that they had only used it as "a last resort".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At a meeting of the Metropolitan Police Authority the following day, the Metropolitan Police's Commissioner Sir Paul Stephenson defended the tactics.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] He was criticised by Jenny Jones, a Green Party member of the London Assembly, who told him: "when you imprison thousands of people, which is essentially what you did yesterday, you do have a duty of care to them...
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] You kept people for nine-and-a-half hours.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A spokesperson for Prime Minister Cameron stated that "people have a right to engage in lawful and peaceful protest, but there is no place for violence or intimidation", while education minister David Willetts responded by claiming that protesting students did not understand the government's plans.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Clegg stated on BBC Radio 2 that "I hate in politics, as in life, to make promises that you then find you can't keep.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] We made a promise we can't deliver – we didn't win the election outright and there are compromises in coalition." Labour Party leader Ed Miliband stated that he would not rule out joining further demonstrations, remarking that "I was quite tempted to go out and talk to them [the protesters].
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Peaceful demonstrations are part of our society.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A third central London protest was organised for Tuesday 30 November, a day that saw cold temperatures and snow in the city.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Protesters assembled at Trafalgar Square, but a police line prevented their march down Whitehall towards the Houses of Parliament; the NCAFC accused the Police of "pre-emptively block[ing]" the protest route.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Fearing that they would be kettled in the Square, protesters dispersed throughout the city center, pursued by police.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Other officers stood photographing and filming the students for later identification, while police vans blocked off certain streets.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Some protesters chanted "Peaceful protest!
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Peaceful protest!" and "no ifs, no buts, no education cuts", and others blew vuvuzelas and played reggae from portable stereo systems.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A BBC reporter talked to members of the demonstration, noting that while many desired a peaceful outcome, others believed that violent confrontation with the police was inevitable.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many were angry with how they had been portrayed in the media, with one commenting that confrontation was not caused by "hardcore anarchists" but by "students who are very, very angry".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many protesters ran onto Pall Mall and then past St James's Park.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Denied access to Parliament Square by police, they turned around and headed toward Westminster Abbey.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A reporter from *The Guardian* noted that "the march is fracturing – people are going up different streets and getting lost.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The police kettled those in the Square, whilst some of the protesters waved banners with slogans such as "Don't put the kettle on, Mr.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Cameron" and "I Can't Believe It's Not Thatcher".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The police "put lines [of officers] across all the exits" to the kettled area of the Square, but reportedly allowed small groups of protesters to leave, even though the majority, around 150 to 200, decided to stay and continue protesting in the snow.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Some protesters burned placards and one spray-painted the word "Revolution" on Nelson's Column.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Others threw plastic bottles and fireworks at police lines, and at one point there "was a scuffle as a knot of policemen rushed one of the protesters, grabbing him to arrest him, and the crowd flocked angrily to the area".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At another time, a group of riot police moved into the crowd of protesters to attempt to secure Nelson's Column, only to be surrounded by demonstrators shouting "Who's kettling who?
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] We're kettling you!" Other slogans shouted at police during the protest included "Shame on you!" and "Your job's next".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police then arrested 146 demonstrators who refused to leave the Square; 139 of them were arrested for breach of the peace, whilst seven were arrested on suspicion of violent disorder.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Seven more had been arrested in central London earlier in the day.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The night before, on 28 November, a crowd of two to three hundred protesters gathered outside of Lewisham Town Hall in Catford, south London, where a council meeting was then in progress, to protest against wider public sector cuts.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several Youtube videos of the incident were shown on national news, including the BBC.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many of the protesters had come from nearby sixth forms (due to potential Education Maintenance Allowance cuts) and also from Goldsmiths College.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Demonstrators, playing music and political slogans from boomboxes forced their way into the building, where a smoke bomb was let off, while another protester climbed onto the roof and unfurled a banner.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several more flares were set off outside and windows smashed, with riot police from the Territorial Support Group close by, were called and several arrests were made.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] One of the protesters, Sue Luxton, a former Green Party councillor who had subsequently become a teacher, told the press that "I wanted to peacefully express my anger at the cuts...
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On the day of the main demonstration, there were also further protests across the United Kingdom, including in Cardiff, Cambridge, Colchester, Newcastle, Bath, Leeds, Sheffield, Edinburgh, Liverpool, Belfast, Brighton, York, Manchester, Plymouth, Scunthorpe and Bristol.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] About 1,500 students, including school children, took part in the protest in Brighton, whilst protests in Bristol involved police being pelted with mustard and ten demonstrators were arrested.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In Sheffield, police were pelted with snowballs as they guarded the constituency office of Nick Clegg from a crowd of two hundred protesters.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The British protests coincided with those in Italy, where demonstrations occurred in Milan, Turin, Naples, Venice, Palermo, Bari, Genoa, and Rome where riot police were called in to prevent students from gaining access to the parliament building.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Meanwhile, whilst occupations that had begun the previous week continued at University College London, Newcastle University and the University of Cambridge, a new one began at the University of Nottingham, where 150 protesters occupied a building.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] University buildings and local government buildings were occupied in Birmingham and Oxford while police blocked an attempt at occupation of the council building in York.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The protesters occupying the council chamber in Birmingham left after four hours, with a police spokesperson commending the protesters for their "wholly peaceful" behaviour, and noting that it "couldn't have been more different from the violent clashes seen recently in London".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] ULU members handed out green hard hats with the words "Tax the banks, not the students" on them, whilst a rally was held in Bloomsbury at midday, where ULU President Solomon addressed the crowd.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police had positioned lines of riot police and police vans along the Houses of Parliament, to prevent any protesters gaining access to it.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Superintendent Julia Pendry issued a statement saying: "Protesters will be allowed sight and sound of parliament.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] However, there is evidence to suggest a number of people will come to London intent on causing violence and disorder.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The protesters marched from Bloomsbury to Parliament Square in the afternoon, where they pushed down metal barriers and occupied the Square.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Around 3:30 pm, police kettled those several thousand protesters in the square, preventing them from leaving, stating that it was necessary "due to the level of violence that our officers are facing".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Mounted police charged into the crowd on one side of the Square in an attempt to disperse them.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A field hospital was set up on the green providing emergency first aid to protesters as well as tea and food within the containment area.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Around 30 protesters were treated, most for head injuries.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police used batons to hit protesters, and a St John Ambulance member told press that he had treated ten protesters for head injuries from being struck by police batons by 4.30 pm.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] One protester, philosophy student Alfie Meadows, suffered a blow to the head from a police truncheon that knocked him unconscious.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Taken to hospital, it was discovered that he was suffering from bleeding of the brain, and required brain surgery.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Reporter Jonathan Haynes of *The Guardian*, who was present, characterised the police tactics as "very heavy handed".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police informed press that they were allowing young and vulnerable protesters to leave the kettle, but those inside the kettle, including journalists, asserted that this was untrue.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At 5:41 pm, news reached the protesters that the government had voted to support the proposals.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Clashes ensued between the crowd and the police, and the protesters pulled along metal fencing to separate themselves from riot police, who were trying to push them all into the centre of the Square.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Later on in the evening, with the protesters still kettled in the Square, protesters smashed all of the windows on the ground floor of Her Majesty's Treasury.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At 21:15, the protest was forced onto Westminster Bridge where it was kettled until approximately 23:30.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Due to the Parliament Square protest being kettled, many other demonstrators could not enter the Square and so disseminated across much of the rest of central London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Meanwhile, many of those students who remained around the area of Trafalgar Square continued to protest, with about 150 holding a sit-in in the adjacent National Gallery, while others attempted to set fire to the Trafalgar Square Christmas tree.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] During the protests, a car taking The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall to the evening's Royal Variety Performance at the London Palladium was attacked on Regent Street and Home Secretary Theresa May confirmed a protester 'made contact' with Camilla.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In Oxford Street, Topshop was damaged, as rioters sprayed "pay your tax" on the building and broke windows.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Home Secretary Theresa May issued a statement in which she "utterly condemned" the actions of the protesters, and declared that "What we are seeing in London tonight, the wanton vandalism, smashing of windows, has nothing to do with peaceful protest...
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Nearly 50 people complained to the Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) about police behaviour during the various protests held around the country, with the majority directed against the Metropolitan Police, including complaints of violence used against protesters.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Following the protests, video footage posted on YouTube showed Jody McIntyre, a protester with cerebral palsy, involved in an altercation with police.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The footage showed McIntyre, who had positioned himself in the front line facing police, being pulled out of his wheelchair and dragged across the ground by Metropolitan Police officers.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] While McIntyre later said he had been pulled out of the wheelchair twice, only one incident is shown in the video.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 13 December, he was interviewed about the incident by BBC journalist Ben Brown, an interview later described by *The Guardian* newspaper as "having a distinct lack of sympathy from the BBC" and it was noted that the incident had "attracted thousands of complaints".
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] McIntyre's complaint was later rejected by Scotland Yard.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] His subsequent appeal was partly upheld by the IPCC.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Street medics treated student protesters during the parliament square protest on Thursday 9 December, the day of the scheduled vote to raise university tuition fees.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A field tent was set up on the green providing emergency first aid to protesters as well as tea and food within the containment area.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Alfie Meadows was acquitted of all charges in 2013.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In September 2023 the Metropolitan Police apologised to him and agreed a financial settlement.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 30 November, following the third main day of protesting, the Welsh Assembly announced that it would not permit an increase in fees for Welsh students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In July 2011, three school children will challenge the kettling of children at the 24 November 2010 protest.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In September 2011, students in Northern Ireland succeeded in getting the Northern Ireland Assembly to freeze tuition fees, avoiding the large fee increases in England.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Student leaders in Northern Ireland cited the wider protests across the UK as one reason for their success.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] As of 2020, this has saved Northern Ireland university students £1 billion in tuition fees compared to English students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In November 2012, two years after the 2010 demonstrations, protests ignited again from the student movement.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Organised by the NUS, around 10,000 demonstrators marched in central London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Cooper complained that the allegations were untrue, threatened his future academic prospects and left his reputation "as badly trashed" as the Millbank Tower.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The years following the student protests saw a leftward shift in the politics of the NUS.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In 2014 the NUS Conference voted in support of free education, reversing the union's previous policy of advocating a graduate tax as a replacement for tuition fees, which it had adopted in the late 2000s.
[src:university-of-cambridge/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Student Broad Left made progressive gains in the mid-2010s, culminating in the election of SBL candidate Malia Bouattia as NUS President.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Romero's *Night of the Living Dead* film series and John Wyndham's 1951 novel *The Day of the Triffids.* Filming took place in various locations in the United Kingdom in 2001.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The crew filmed for brief periods during early mornings and temporarily closed streets in London to capture recognizable and typically busy areas when they were deserted.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] John Murphy composed an original soundtrack for the film, with other instrumental songs by Brian Eno, Godspeed You!
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Despite Boyle not considering it a zombie film, *28 Days Later* is credited with reinvigorating the genre and influencing a revival in it a decade after its release, with its fast-running infected and character-driven drama.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] It has been featured in several "best-of" film lists.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The film's success launched its titular film series, featuring three further instalments: *28 Weeks Later* (2007), *28 Years Later* (2025), and *28 Years Later: The Bone Temple* (2026).
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] A wider franchise also includes the graphic novel *28 Days Later: The Aftermath* (2007), and the comic book series *28 Days Later* (2009–2011).
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] A group of animal rights activists infiltrate a laboratory in Cambridge which houses abnormally aggressive chimpanzees.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Despite a scientist warning that the chimpanzees are "infected" with "rage", an activist frees one; it attacks her and, within seconds of exposure, she succumbs to the virus.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] She immediately attacks the others, and the virus spreads rapidly across Great Britain, resulting in total societal collapse.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Twenty-eight days later, bicycle courier Jim, who had a traffic accident and fell into a coma before the outbreak, wakes in St Thomas' Hospital in London to find it deserted.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Leaving the hospital, Jim wanders the empty streets of London, discovers newspapers headlining a mass evacuation, and eventually enters a church and witnesses the aftermath of a massacre, presumably caused by the infected people.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] An infected priest and members of the public appear and chase after Jim, but he is rescued by survivors Selena and Mark, who take him to their refuge in a Tube station shop.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] At Jim's request, the group travels on foot to his parents' house in Deptford, where he learns that they have died by suicide, leaving a note instructing him to "never wake up".
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] When dusk settles in, the group decides to stay the night.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Staying up, Jim reminisces over family memories and lights a candle, drawing the infected neighbours to the house.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Mark is infected while eliminating them, forcing Selena to kill him.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Jim and Selena make their way up Balfron Tower after seeing a makeshift signal lamp in a flat belonging to cab driver Frank and his young daughter Hannah.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Frank plays them a military radio broadcast offering protection and "salvation from infection" at a blockade outside Manchester.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Frank plans to take Hannah to the blockade, and the four agree to travel together.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Reaching Manchester, they find the blockade deserted.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Frank, frustrated, kicks a gate on which a dead infected body is balanced.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] A drop of blood from the corpse falls into Frank's eye, infecting him.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] As he warns the others to keep their distance, hidden soldiers appear and shoot him dead as he turns.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The soldiers bring Jim, Selena and Hannah to a heavily fortified country house under the command of Major Henry West, treat their guests to a tour and banquet and introduces him to "Private Mailer", an infected soldier kept chained up for observation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] However, the sanctuary turns out to be a ruse; West reveals to Jim that his broadcast was intended to lure female survivors into sexual slavery to maintain his troops' morale, giving them faith in a future where the human race survives.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Jim and Sergeant Farrell refuse to go along with this scheme, so West orders them to be imprisoned.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] While chained, Farrell tells Jim that the infection has not spread across the Atlantic and that Britain has been quarantined from the rest of the world.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Two soldiers shoot Farrell and then argue, allowing Jim to escape into the woods.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Jim notices a jet contrail in the sky, showing proof that the outside world is still active.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] After luring West away from the mansion with a siren, Jim returns and frees Private Mailer in order to infect and kill the remaining soldiers.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Corporal Mitchell attempts to abduct Selena, but Jim kills him.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Jim, Selena, and Hannah attempt to escape in Frank's cab, but West, who has hidden in the back seat, shoots Jim in the stomach.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Hannah retaliates by putting the cab in reverse, causing Mailer to burst through the rear window and drag West out before mauling him to death as the car drives away.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Another twenty-eight days later, Jim recovers at a remote cottage in Cumbria, where the infected are shown lying on the roads, dying of starvation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] As a Hawker Hunter jet flies overhead, Jim, Selena, and Hannah unfurl a huge cloth banner spelling the word "HELLO".
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] All three survivors wave at the jet, and wonder among themselves if the pilot has spotted them.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Additionally, Alex Palmer, Bindu De Stoppani, and Jukka Hiltunen portray the animal liberation activists, while David Schneider portrays a scientist at the laboratory.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Christopher Dunne and Emma Hitching appear as Jim's parents.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Toby Sedgwick plays an infected priest encountered by Jim.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Sedgwick would later return to the series in a behind the scenes role, acting as the movement coach for *28 Years Later* (2025).
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Early influences on writer Alex Garland included the George A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Romero films *Night of the Living Dead* (1968) and *Dawn of the Dead* (1978), which he loved as a child.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Garland claimed to have largely forgotten about the zombie genre until he played the video game *Resident Evil* (1996), which reminded him how much he loved zombies after "having not really encountered zombies for quite a while".
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Director Danny Boyle liked Garland's screenplay for a proposed zombie film, having directed the 2000 film adaptation of Garland's 1996 novel *The Beach*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Rather than portraying zombies as supernatural beings, the film's rage virus was conceived as a biological contagion.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle and Garland intended the virus to amplify an inherent aspect of human nature—psychological aggression—depicting rage as an uncontrollable viral force intrinsic to humanity rather than merely a physical infection.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] This was designed to serve as a metaphor for contemporary social rage, including road rage, air rage, and other everyday aggressive behaviours.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Garland described the supermarket sequence as a deliberate nod to Romero's *Dawn of the Dead*, and the chained Infected as a nod to the character "Bub" in *Day of the Dead*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Garland said he was thinking of the plantation dinner sequence from *Apocalypse Now Redux* when writing the soldiers' dinner scene.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Producer Andrew Macdonald had access to funding from the National Lottery and pitched it to Universal Pictures, who declined to support it.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Budget constraints proved to be an issue, with Christopher Eccleston having to take an emergency pay cut.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] In June 2001, it was reported that Fox Searchlight Pictures had picked up for co-financing as well as worldwide distribution.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle identified John Wyndham's 1951 novel *The Day of the Triffids* as Garland's original inspiration for the story.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Five months after the film was released in Europe, video game publisher NovaLogic hosted a graffiti competition in a cross-promotion with the game *Devastation* (2003).
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The connection was owed mainly to the similar theme of a devastated world.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The prizes consisted of signed screenplay copies and posters along with DVDs.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] For the Infected, Boyle took inspiration from real-life diseases, particularly Ebola, with aspects of rabies.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] On the DVD commentary, Boyle explains that with the aim of preserving the suspension of disbelief, relatively unknown actors were cast in the film.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Cillian Murphy had starred primarily in small independent films, while Naomie Harris had acted on British television as a child, and Megan Burns had only one previous film credit.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] However, Christopher Eccleston and Brendan Gleeson were well-known character actors.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Murphy originally auditioned for the role with a modern Received Pronunciation accent, as Jim was written to be English.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] However, during filming, Boyle and Murphy decided to revert to the actor's natural accent, and rewrote the character as Irish.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] James McAvoy auditioned for a role as an Infected.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The film features scenes set in normally bustling parts of London, such as Westminster Bridge, Piccadilly Circus, Horse Guards Parade and Oxford Street.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] To depict these locations as desolate, the film crew closed off sections of street for minutes at a time, usually on Sunday mornings.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] They typically had around 45 minutes after dawn to shoot the locations devoid of members of the public and traffic, with closures lasting only "90 seconds or two minutes" at a time while traffic was held back by volunteer marshals (students and friends).
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle said the early London sequences avoided "litter[ing] the world with corpses", instead emphasising a more symbolic emptiness and atmosphere.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The scenes of the empty M1 motorway were also filmed within limited periods; Boyle said police created a "rolling block" in both directions to produce a temporary corridor of empty road, giving the crew seven or eight minutes to shoot using multiple cameras.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] For the London scene in which Jim walks by an overturned double-decker bus, the film crew placed the bus on its side and removed it when the shot was finished, all within about 15–20 minutes.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The crew had asked Westminster City Council for permission to place the bus outside Downing Street, which was denied; when they arrived there at 4am and nobody from the council was present, they placed the bus there anyway.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The September 11 attacks took place during filming.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle notes the parallel between the "missing persons" flyers seen at the beginning of the film and similar flyers posted in New York City in the wake of the attacks.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle said his crew probably would not have been granted permission to close off Whitehall for filming after the terrorist attacks, citing the production's ability to stage an overturned bus there before the attacks.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The mansion used in the film was Trafalgar Park near Salisbury.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The old ruins used as the setting for an idyllic interlude in their journey to Manchester were those of Waverley Abbey, Surrey.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The end scenes of the film with Jim, Selena and Hannah living in a rural cottage were filmed around Ennerdale in Cumbria.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The production team hired an optometrist to supervise with the red contact lenses needed for cast members playing the infected.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle said the supermarket scene was filmed overnight at a Budgens on Tottenham Court Road using the store's overhead lighting; to save time, the crew avoided neon where possible and had the visual-effects house Clear paint out remaining neon in post-production.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle said some pick-ups were shot by cinematographer Alwin Küchler because Anthony Dod Mantle was unavailable.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle said the film initially ended with Jim being shot, which marked the end of the first budget; after showing the cut to Fox, the production received additional funding and shot the final sequence months later.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] After several different pitches for a new ending, with the original ending which featured Jim's death having tested badly with audiences, the studio approved the ending eventually used.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The crew arranged for a real jet to fly overhead for them to film, as this was cheaper than approximately £70,000 for a computer-generated one.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle said Fox funded the Lake District ending, and that the final rural sequence was shot on 35mm to make the film "feel like [it] had opened up".
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Boyle said the overflight was filmed with an RAF jet standing in for the Finnish Air Force, and that the markings could not be changed.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The DVD extras include three alternative endings, all of which conclude with Jim dying.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The first alternate ending involves Jim dying of his gunshot wounds in a hospital despite Selena and Hannah's efforts to save him, concluding with the two of them leaving the hospital to an unknown fate.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The US cinematic release included this ending after the film's credits in response to intense online debates over whether or not it was a more appropriate conclusion than the official ending.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] In the second, Jim dreams of the accident that left him in a coma as he dies from his gunshot wounds.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] This ending was never filmed due to Boyle and Garland agreeing that it lacked plausibility.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The film's score was composed by John Murphy, featuring electric guitar and atmospheric electronic production.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] It also features tracks from Brian Eno, Grandaddy and Blue States, and was released in a combined score and song compilation in 2003.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] A heavily edited version of the track "East Hastings" by the post-rock band Godspeed You!
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Black Emperor appears in the film, but the track is excluded from the soundtrack, because Boyle could only obtain the rights to use it in the film.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Critical views of the film were positive.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] On the film review aggregator Rotten Tomatoes, 87% of 240 critics' reviews gave *28 Days Later* a positive review, with an average rating of 7.60/10.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The site's consensus reads: "Kinetically directed by Danny Boyle, *28 Days Later* is both a terrifying zombie movie and a sharp political allegory." On Metacritic, the film received a rating of 73 out of 100 based on 39 reviews, indicating "generally favourable reviews".
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The film was notorious for being largely unavailable to purchase on home video, attributed to out-of-print copies and expensive secondhand prices of the film on Blu-ray, DVD and VHS, as well as its unavailability on digital.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] In December 2024, following a largely favourable response from the public to the trailer for *28 Years Later*, Sony announced that it would be making *28 Days Later* available for purchase on digital and rental platforms from December 18.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The following year, Sony Pictures Home Entertainment announced a 4K remaster of the film to be released with a steelbook cover, which was later announced to be scheduled for a September 1, 2026 release.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] During the COVID-19 pandemic, images of a national lockdown in the United Kingdom and stay-at-home orders elsewhere were compared to the opening sequence of *28 Days Later*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] In 2021, Megan Burns said of the film, "When I joined the cast of *28 Days Later* I had no idea of how big a cultural impact it would have and what a game-changer it would be to the 'zombie' genre.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Even now after all these years, (or perhaps especially now with the current situation), people want to talk about the film and that's incredible." Christopher Nolan said he cast Murphy as Scarecrow in *Batman Begins* (2005) after being impressed by his performance in *28 Days Later*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] A sequel, *28 Weeks Later*, was released on 11 May 2007.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Danny Boyle and Alex Garland took producing roles alongside Andrew Macdonald.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The plot revolves around the arrival of American troops about seven months after the incidents in the original film, attempting to restore order and revitalise a nearly desolate Britain.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The cast includes Robert Carlyle, Rose Byrne, Jeremy Renner, Imogen Poots, Harold Perrineau, Catherine McCormack, Mackintosh Muggleton and Idris Elba.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] A third film, *28 Years Later*, was released on 20 June 2025, its development having been announced in January 2024.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Danny Boyle had said in March 2007 that he would be interested in making a third film in the series, *28 Months Later*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] In 2019, he said "Alex Garland and I have a wonderful idea for the third part".
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] *28 Years Later* is considered the first instalment in a potential trilogy, with Boyle directing the first film and Garland writing all three.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] With a planned $75 million budget per instalment, the duo will also produce the trilogy alongside the original producer Andrew Macdonald and former Fox Searchlight Pictures head Peter Rice.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The fourth film, *28 Years Later: The Bone Temple*, was directed by Nia DaCosta and filmed back-to-back with its predecessor.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] It premiered in the United Kingdom on 13 January 2026 as part of a double feature with *28 Years Later*, followed by individual releases in the UK on 14 January and the United States on 16 January.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The plot continues the narrative of the previous film and reintroduces the character portrayed by Cillian Murphy from *28 Days Later*, setting up the fifth instalment of the franchise.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Following the success of *28 Years Later* and *The Bone Temple*, Sony confirmed that the third and final film of the planned *28 Years Later* trilogy is in development, with Danny Boyle returning as director and Alex Garland writing.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] In 2007, Fox Atomic Comics, in association with HarperCollins, published *28 Days Later: The Aftermath*, a graphic novel written by Steve Niles.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The work serves as a tie-in to the films, depicting events surrounding the Rage virus outbreak and providing background that connects *28 Days Later* with its sequel *28 Weeks Later*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] A separate monthly comic book series, also titled *28 Days Later*, was launched in 2009 by Boom!
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] Studios following the closure of Fox Atomic.
[src:university-of-cambridge/28-days-later] The series continues the story of Selena, one of the film's central characters, and explores her actions and whereabouts between the events of the two films.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne was the father of bookseller Christopher Robin Milne, upon whom the character Christopher Robin is based.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] It was during a visit to London Zoo, where Christopher became enamoured of the tame and amiable bear Winnipeg, that Milne was inspired to write the story of Winnie-the-Pooh for his son.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne bequeathed the original manuscripts of the Winnie-the-Pooh stories to the Wren Library at Trinity College, Cambridge, his alma mater.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Alan Alexander Milne was born in Kilburn, London, to John Vine Milne, who was born in Jamaica, and Sarah Marie Milne (née Heginbotham), on 18 January 1882.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He grew up at Henley House School, 6/7 Mortimer Road (now Crescent), Kilburn, a small independent school run by his father.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He taught himself to read at the age of two.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne attended Westminster School and Trinity College, Cambridge, where he studied on a mathematics scholarship, graduating with a Bachelor of Arts in Mathematics in 1903, though he was always interested in writing.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He edited and wrote for *Granta*, a student magazine.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He collaborated with his brother Kenneth and their articles appeared over the initials AKM.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne's work came to the attention of the leading British humour magazine *Punch*, where Milne was to become a contributor and later an assistant editor.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Considered a talented cricket fielder, Milne played for two amateur teams that were largely composed of British writers: the Allahakbarries and the Authors XI.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] His teammates included fellow writers J.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne joined the British Army during World War I and served as an officer in the Royal Warwickshire Regiment.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He was commissioned into the 4th Battalion, Royal Warwickshire Regiment, on 1 February 1915 as a second lieutenant (on probation).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] His commission was confirmed on 20 December 1915.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He served on the Somme as a signals officer from July–November 1916, but caught trench fever and was invalided back to England.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Having recuperated, he worked as a signals instructor, before being recruited into military intelligence to write propaganda articles for MI7 (b) between 1917 and 1918.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He was discharged on 14 February 1919, and settled in Mallord Street, Chelsea.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He relinquished his commission on 19 February 1920, retaining the rank of lieutenant.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] After the war, he wrote a denunciation of war titled *Peace with Honour* (1934), which he retracted somewhat with 1940's *War with Honour*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] During World War II, Milne was one of the most prominent critics of fellow English writer (and Authors XI cricket teammate) P.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Wodehouse, who was captured at his country home in France by the Nazis and imprisoned for a year.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Wodehouse made radio broadcasts about his internment, which were broadcast from Berlin.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Although the light-hearted broadcasts made fun of the Germans, Milne accused Wodehouse of committing an act of near treason by cooperating with his country's enemy.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Wodehouse got some revenge on his former friend (e.g. in *The Mating Season*) by creating fatuous parodies of the Christopher Robin poems in some of his later stories, and claiming that Milne "was probably jealous of all other writers....
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne married Dorothy "Daphne" de Sélincourt (1890–1971) in 1913 and their son Christopher Robin Milne was born in 1920.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In 1925, Milne bought a country home, Cotchford Farm, in Hartfield, East Sussex.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] During World War II, Milne was a captain in the British Home Guard in Hartfield & Forest Row, insisting on being plain "Mr.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He retired to the farm after a stroke and brain surgery in 1952 left him an invalid; and by August 1953, "he seemed very old and disenchanted." Milne died in January 1956, aged 74.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] After graduating from Cambridge University in 1903, A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne contributed humorous verse and whimsical essays to *Punch*, joining the staff in 1906 and becoming an assistant editor.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] During this period he published 18 plays and three novels, including the murder mystery *The Red House Mystery* (1922).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] His son was born in August 1920 and in 1924 Milne produced a collection of children's poems, *When We Were Very Young*, which were illustrated by *Punch* staff cartoonist E.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] A collection of short stories for children *A Gallery of Children*, and other stories that became part of the Winnie-the-Pooh books, were first published in 1925.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne was an early screenwriter for the nascent British film industry, writing four stories filmed in 1920 for the company Minerva Films (founded in 1920 by the actor Leslie Howard and his friend and story editor Adrian Brunel).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] These were *The Bump*, starring Aubrey Smith; *Twice Two*; *Five Pound Reward*; and *Bookworms*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Some of these films survive in the archives of the British Film Institute.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne had met Howard when the actor starred in Milne's play *Mr Pim Passes By* in London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne is most famous for his two *Pooh* books about a boy named Christopher Robin after his son, Christopher Robin Milne (1920–1996), and various characters inspired by his son's stuffed animals, most notably the bear named Winnie-the-Pooh.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Christopher Robin Milne's stuffed bear, originally named Edward, was renamed Winnie after a Canadian black bear named Winnie (after Winnipeg), which was used as a military mascot in World War I, and left to London Zoo during the war.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] "The Pooh" comes from a swan the young Milne named "Pooh".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Shepard illustrated the original Pooh books, using his own son's teddy Growler ("a magnificent bear") as the model.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The rest of Christopher Robin Milne's toys, Piglet, Eeyore, Kanga, Roo and Tigger, were incorporated into A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne's stories, and two more characters – Rabbit and Owl – were created by Milne's imagination.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Christopher Robin Milne's own toys are now on display in New York where 750,000 people visit them every year.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The fictional Hundred Acre Wood of the Pooh stories derives from Five Hundred Acre Wood in Ashdown Forest in East Sussex, South East England, where the Pooh stories were set.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Shepard drew on the landscapes of Ashdown Forest as inspiration for many of the illustrations he provided for the Pooh books.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Not yet known as Pooh, he made his first appearance in a poem, "Teddy Bear", published in *Punch* magazine in February 1924 and republished that year in *When We Were Very Young*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Pooh first appeared in the *London Evening News* on Christmas Eve, 1925, in a story called "The Wrong Sort of Bees".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] *Winnie-the-Pooh* was published in 1926, followed by *The House at Pooh Corner* in 1928.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] A second collection of nursery rhymes, *Now We Are Six*, was published in 1927.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne also published four plays in this period.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He also "gallantly stepped forward" to contribute a quarter of the costs of dramatising P.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] *The World of Pooh* won the Lewis Carroll Shelf Award in 1958.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] But once Milne had, in his own words, "said goodbye to all that in 70,000 words" (the approximate length of his four principal children's books), he had no intention of producing any reworkings lacking in originality, given that one of the sources of inspiration, his son, was growing older.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Another reason Milne stopped writing children's books, and especially about Winnie-the-Pooh, was that he felt "amazement and disgust" over the immense fame his son was exposed to, and said that "I feel that the legal Christopher Robin has already had more publicity than I want for him.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In his literary home, *Punch*, where the *When We Were Very Young* verses first appeared, Methuen continued to publish whatever Milne wrote, including the long poem "The Norman Church" and an assembly of articles entitled *Year In, Year Out* (which Milne likened to a benefit night for the author).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In 1929, Milne adapted Kenneth Grahame's novel *The Wind in the Willows* for the stage as *Toad of Toad Hall*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The title was an implicit admission that such chapters as Chapter 7, "The Piper at the Gates of Dawn," could not survive translation to the theatre.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] A special introduction written by Milne is included in some editions of Grahame's novel.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] It was first performed at the Playhouse Theatre, Liverpool, on 21 December 1929 before it made its West End debut the following year at the Lyric Theatre on 17 December 1930.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The play was revived in the West End from 1931 to 1935, and since the 1960s there have been West End revivals during the Christmas season; actors who have performed in the play include Judi Dench and Ian McKellen.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne and his wife became estranged from their son, who came to resent what he saw as his father's exploitation of his childhood and came to hate the books that had thrust him into the public eye.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Christopher's marriage to his first cousin, Lesley de Sélincourt, distanced him still further from his parents – Lesley's father and Christopher's mother had not spoken to each other for 30 years.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne died at his home in Hartfield, Sussex, on 31 January 1956, 13 days after his 74th birthday.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] A memorial service took place on 10 February at All Hallows-by-the-Tower church in London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne's Pooh books were left to four beneficiaries: his family, the Royal Literary Fund, Westminster School and the Garrick Club.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] After Milne's death in 1956, his widow sold her rights to the Pooh characters to Stephen Slesinger, whose widow sold the rights after Slesinger's death to Walt Disney Productions, which has made many Pooh cartoon movies, a Disney Channel television show, as well as Pooh-related merchandise.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In 2001, the other beneficiaries sold their interest in the estate to the Disney Corporation for $350m.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Previously Disney had been paying twice-yearly royalties to these beneficiaries.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Shepard also received a sum in the deal.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The UK copyright on the text of the original Winnie the Pooh books expires on 1 January 2027; at the beginning of the year after the 70th anniversary of the author's death (PMA-70), and has already expired in those countries with a PMA-60 rule.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] This applies to all of Milne's works except those first published posthumously.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The illustrations in the Pooh books will remain under copyright until the same amount of time after the illustrator's death has passed; in the UK, this will be 1 January 2047.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In the US, copyright on the four children's books (including the illustrations) expired 95 years after publication of each of the books.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Specifically: copyright on the book *When We Were Very Young* expired in 2020; copyright on the book *Winnie-the-Pooh* expired in 2022; copyright on the book *Now We Are Six* expired in 2023; and copyright on the book *The House at Pooh Corner* expired in 2024.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In 2008, a collection of original illustrations featuring Winnie-the-Pooh and his animal friends sold for more than £1.2 million at auction at Sotheby's, London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] *Forbes* magazine ranked Winnie the Pooh the most valuable fictional character in 2002; Winnie the Pooh merchandising products alone had annual sales of more than $5.9 billion.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In 2005, Winnie the Pooh generated $6 billion, a figure surpassed only by Mickey Mouse.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] A memorial plaque in Ashdown Forest, unveiled by Christopher Robin in 1979, commemorates the work of A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne and Shepard in creating the world of Pooh.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The inscription states they "captured the magic of Ashdown Forest, and gave it to the world".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In 2003, *Winnie-the-Pooh* was ranked number 7 on the BBC's The Big Read poll which determined the UK's "best-loved novels".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In 2006, Winnie-the-Pooh received a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame, marking the 80th birthday of Milne's creation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Marking the 90th anniversary of Milne's creation of the character, and the 90th birthday of Queen Elizabeth II, *Winnie-the-Pooh Meets the Queen* (2016) sees Pooh meet the Queen at Buckingham Palace.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The illustrated and audio adventure is narrated by the actor Jim Broadbent.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Also in 2016, a new character, a Penguin, was unveiled in *The Best Bear in All the World*, which was inspired by a long-lost photograph of Milne and his son Christopher with a toy penguin.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] An exhibition entitled *Winnie-the-Pooh: Exploring a Classic* appeared at the Victoria and Albert Museum in London from 9 December 2017 to 8 April 2018.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The composer Harold Fraser-Simson, a near neighbour, produced six books of Milne songs between 1924 and 1932.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The poems have been parodied many times, including in the books *When We Were Rather Older* and *Now We Are Sixty*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The 1963 film *The King's Breakfast* was based on Milne's poem of the same name.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne has been portrayed in television and film.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Domhnall Gleeson plays him in *Goodbye Christopher Robin*, a 2017 biographical drama film.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] In the 2018 fantasy film *Christopher Robin*, an extension of the Disney Winnie the Pooh franchise, Tristan Sturrock plays Milne, and filming took place at Ashdown Forest.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] An elementary school in Houston, Texas, operated by the Houston Independent School District (HISD), is named after Milne.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne Elementary School in Brays Oaks, opened in 1991.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The original manuscripts for *Winnie-the-Pooh* and *The House at Pooh Corner* are archived at Trinity College Library, Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne's papers are housed at the Harry Ransom Center at the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The collection, established at the centre in 1964, consists of manuscript drafts and fragments for over 150 of Milne's works, as well as correspondence, legal documents, genealogical records, and some personal effects.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The library division holds several books formerly belonging to Milne and his wife Dorothy.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] The center also has small collections of correspondence from Christopher Robin Milne and Milne's frequent illustrator E.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] Milne did not speak out much on the subject of religion, although he used religious terms to explain his decision, while remaining a pacifist, to join the British Home Guard.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-a-milne] He wrote: "In fighting Hitler we are truly fighting the Devil, the Anti-Christ ...
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In 1896, Housman published *A Shropshire Lad*, a cycle of poems marked by the author's pessimism and preoccupation with early death, which gradually acquired a wide readership and appealed particularly to a younger audience during World War I.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Another collection, entitled *Last Poems*, appeared in 1922.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman's poetry became popular for musical settings.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Following his death, further poems from his notebooks were published by his brother Laurence, titled *More Poems* (1936).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman's *A Shropshire Lad* includes some iconic individual poems like "Loveliest of trees, the cherry now" (II), "When I was one-and-twenty" (XIII), "Is my team ploughing" (XXVII) and "Into my heart an air that kills" (XL).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] His mother died on his twelfth birthday, and his father, a country solicitor, then married an elder cousin, Lucy, in 1873.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Two of his siblings became prominent writers, sister Clemence Housman and brother Laurence Housman.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman was educated at King Edward's School in Birmingham and later Bromsgrove School, where he revealed his academic promise and won prizes for his poems.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In 1877, he won an open scholarship to St John's College, Oxford, and went there to study classics.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Although introverted by nature, Housman formed strong friendships with two roommates, Moses John Jackson (1858–1923) and A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Though Housman obtained a first in classical Moderations in 1879, his dedication to textual analysis led him to neglect the ancient history and philosophy that formed part of the Greats curriculum.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Accordingly, he failed the Finals and had to return humiliated in Michaelmas term to resit the exam so as to at least gain a lower-level pass degree.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Though some attribute Housman's unexpected performance in his exams directly to his unrequited feelings for Jackson, most biographers adduce more obvious causes.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman was indifferent to philosophy and overconfident in his exceptional gifts and he spent too much time with his friends.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He may also have been distracted by news of his father's desperate illness.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] After Oxford, Jackson went to work as a clerk in the Patent Office in London and he also arranged a job there for Housman.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The two shared a flat at 82 Talbot Road, Bayswater, with Jackson's brother Adalbert until 1885, when Housman moved to lodgings of his own, probably after Jackson responded to a declaration of love by telling Housman that he could not reciprocate his feelings.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Two years later, Jackson moved to India, placing more distance between himself and Housman.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] When he returned briefly to England in 1889 to marry, Housman was not invited to the wedding and knew nothing about it until the couple had left the country.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Adalbert Jackson died in 1892 and Housman commemorated him in a poem published as "XLII – A.J.J." of *More Poems* (1936).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Meanwhile, Housman pursued his classical studies independently, and published scholarly articles on Horace, Propertius, Ovid, Aeschylus, Euripides and Sophocles.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He also completed an edition of Propertius, which however was rejected by both Oxford University Press and Macmillan in 1885, and was destroyed after his death.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He gradually acquired such a high reputation that in 1892 he was offered and accepted the professorship of Latin at University College London (UCL).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] When, during his tenure, an immensely rare Coverdale Bible of 1535 was discovered in the UCL library and presented to the Library Committee, Housman (who had become an atheist while at Oxford) remarked that it would be better to sell it to "buy some really useful books with the proceeds".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Although Housman's early work and his responsibilities as a professor included both Latin and Greek, he began to specialise in Latin poetry.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] When asked later why he had stopped writing about Greek verse, he responded, "I found that I could not attain to excellence in both." In 1911 he took the Kennedy Professorship of Latin at Trinity College, Cambridge, where he remained for the rest of his life.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Between 1903 and 1930, Housman published his critical edition of Manilius's *Astronomicon* in five volumes.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He also edited Juvenal (1905) and Lucan (1926).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He was and may remain the last great textual critic".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In the eyes of Harry Eyres, however, Housman was "famously dry" as a professor, and his influence led to a scholarly style in the study of literature and poetry that was philological and without emotion.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Many colleagues were unnerved by Housman's scathing attacks on those he thought guilty of shoddy scholarship.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In his paper "The Application of Thought to Textual Criticism" (1921) he wrote: "A textual critic engaged upon his business is not at all like Newton investigating the motion of the planets: he is much more like a dog hunting for fleas".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He declared many of his contemporary scholars to be stupid, lazy, vain, or all three, saying: "Knowledge is good, method is good, but one thing beyond all others is necessary; and that is to have a head, not a pumpkin, on your shoulders, and brains, not pudding, in your head".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Gow, quoted examples of these attacks, noting that they "were often savage in the extreme".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Gow also related how Housman intimidated students, sometimes reducing the women to tears.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] According to Gow, Housman could never remember the names of female students, maintaining that "had he burdened his memory by the distinction between Miss Jones and Miss Robinson, he might have forgotten that between the second and fourth declension".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Among the more notable students at his Cambridge lectures was Enoch Powell, one of whose own Classical emendations was later complimented by Housman.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In his private life, Housman enjoyed country walks, gastronomy, air travel and making frequent visits to France, where he read "books which were banned in Britain as pornographic" but he struck A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Benson, a fellow don, as being "descended from a long line of maiden aunts".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] His feelings about his poetry were ambivalent and he certainly treated it as secondary to his scholarship.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He did not speak in public about his poems until 1933, when he gave a lecture "The Name and Nature of Poetry", arguing there that poetry should appeal to emotions rather than to the intellect.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] His ashes are buried just outside St Laurence's Church, Ludlow.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] A cherry tree was planted there in his memory (see *A Shropshire Lad* II) and replaced by the Housman Society in 2003 with a new cherry tree nearby.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In the same vein, Harry Eyres interpreted it as "what you could see as an act of self-punishment" that so many years were devoted to "a minor Roman versifier whose long didactic poem on astrology must rank as one of the most obscure in the entire annals of poetry".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] During his years in London, Housman completed *A Shropshire Lad*, a cycle of 63 poems.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] After one publisher had turned it down, he helped subsidise its publication in 1896.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] At first selling slowly, it rapidly became a lasting success.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Its appeal to English musicians had helped to make it widely known before World War I, when its themes struck a powerful chord with English readers.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The book has been in print continuously since May 1896.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The poems are marked by pessimism and preoccupation with death, without religious consolation (Housman had become an atheist while still an undergraduate).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman wrote many of them while living in Highgate, London, before ever visiting Shropshire, which he presented in an idealised pastoral light as his 'land of lost content'.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman himself acknowledged that "No doubt I have been unconsciously influenced by the Greeks and Latins, but [the] chief sources of which I am conscious are Shakespeare's songs, the Scottish Border ballads, and Heine".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman began collecting a new set of poems after the First World War.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] His early work was an influence on many British poets who became famous by their writing about the war, and he wrote several poems as occasional verse to commemorate the war dead.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] This included his *Epitaph on an Army of Mercenaries*, honouring the British Expeditionary Force, an elite but small force of professional soldiers sent to Belgium at the start of the war.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In the early 1920s, when Moses Jackson was dying in Canada, Housman wanted to assemble his best unpublished poems so that Jackson could read them before his death.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] These later poems, mostly written before 1910, show a greater variety of subject and form than those in *A Shropshire Lad* but lack its consistency.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He published his new collection as *Last Poems* (1922), feeling that his inspiration was exhausted and that he should not publish more in his lifetime.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] After Housman's death in 1936, his brother, Laurence published further poems in *More Poems* (1936), *A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] E .H.: Some Poems, Some Letters and a Personal Memoir by his Brother* (1937), and *Collected Poems* (1939).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] H.* includes humorous verse such as a parody of Longfellow's poem *Excelsior*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman also wrote a parodic *Fragment of a Greek Tragedy*, in English, first published in 1883 in *The Bromsgrovian*, the magazine of his old school, and frequently reprinted.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Sparrow himself adds, "How difficult it is to achieve a satisfactory analysis may be judged by considering the last poem in *A Shropshire Lad*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Of its four stanzas, Housman tells us that two were 'given' him ready made; one was coaxed forth from his subconsciousness an hour or two later; the remaining one took months of conscious composition.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In 1942, Laurence Housman also deposited an essay entitled "A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman's 'De Amicitia'" in the British Library, with the proviso that it was not to be published for 25 years.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman's homosexuality and his love for Moses Jackson.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Despite the conservative nature of the times and his own caution in public life, Housman was quite open in his poetry, and especially in *A Shropshire Lad*, about his deeper sympathies.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Poem XXX of that sequence, for instance, speaks of how "Fear contended with desire": "Others, I am not the first, / Have willed more mischief than they durst".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] His poem "Oh who is that young sinner with the handcuffs on his wrists?", written after the trial of Oscar Wilde, addressed more general attitudes towards homosexuals.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] This refers to an old paraphrasing for homosexuality in English law.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman's poetry, especially *A Shropshire Lad*, was set to music by many British, and in particular English, composers in the first half of the 20th century.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The national, pastoral and traditional elements of his style resonated with similar trends in English music.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In 1904, the cycle *A Shropshire Lad* was set by Arthur Somervell, who in 1898 had begun to develop the concept of the English song-cycle in his version of Tennyson's "Maud".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Stephen Banfield believes it was acquaintance with Somervell's cycle that led other composers to set Housman: Ralph Vaughan Williams is likely to have attended the first performance at the Aeolian Hall on 3 February 1905.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] His well-known cycle of six songs *On Wenlock Edge*, for string quartet, tenor and piano, was published in 1909.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Between 1909 and 1911, George Butterworth produced settings in two collections, *Six Songs from A Shropshire Lad* and *Bredon Hill and Other Songs*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He also wrote the orchestral tone poem *A Shropshire Lad*, first performed at Leeds Festival in 1912.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Ivor Gurney was another composer who made renowned settings of Housman's poems.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Towards the end of World War I, he was working on his cycle *Ludlow and Teme*, for voice and string quartet (published in 1919), and went on to compose the eight-song cycle *The Western Playland* in 1921.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] One more who set Housman songs during this period was John Ireland in the song cycle, *The Land of Lost Content* (1920–21).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Charles Wilfred Orr produced 24 Housman settings in songs and song cycles composed from the 1920s into the 1950s.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Even composers not directly associated with the 'pastoral' tradition, such as Arnold Bax, Lennox Berkeley and Arthur Bliss, were attracted to Housman's poetry.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Housman's attitude to musical interpretations of his poetry, and indeed to music in general, was either indifference or torment.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] He told his friend Percy Withers that he knew nothing of music and it meant nothing to him.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Withers once played him a record of the Vaughan Williams setting, but realised he had made a mistake when he saw the look of disgust on the poet's face.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Nevertheless, by 1976, a catalogue listed 400 musical settings of Housman's poems.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] As of 2024, Lieder Net Archive records 678 settings of 188 texts.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The earliest commemoration of Housman was in the chapel of Trinity College in Cambridge, where there is a memorial brass on the south wall.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The Latin inscription was composed by his colleague there, A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Gow, who was also the author of a biographical and bibliographical sketch published immediately following his death.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] From 1947, University College London's academic common room was dedicated to his memory as the Housman Room.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Blue plaques followed later elsewhere, the first being on Byron Cottage in Highgate in 1969, recording the fact that *A Shropshire Lad* was written there.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] More followed, placed on his Worcestershire birthplace, his homes and school in Bromsgrove.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The latter were encouraged by the Housman Society, which was founded in the town in 1973.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Another initiative was the statue in Bromsgrove High Street, showing the poet striding with walking stick in hand.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The work of local sculptor Kenneth Potts, it was unveiled on 22 March 1985.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The blue plaques in Worcestershire were set up on the centenary of *A Shropshire Lad* in 1996.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] In September of the same year, a memorial window lozenge was dedicated at Poets' Corner in Westminster Abbey.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The following year saw the première of Tom Stoppard's play *The Invention of Love*, whose subject is the relationship between Housman and Moses Jackson.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] As the 150th anniversary of his birth approached, London University inaugurated its Housman lectures on classical subjects in 2005, initially given every second year then annually after 2011.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] The anniversary itself in 2009 saw the publication of a new edition of *A Shropshire Lad*, including pictures from across Shropshire taken by local photographer Gareth Thomas.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] Among other events, there were performances of Vaughan Williams's *On Wenlock Edge* and Ivor Gurney's *Ludlow and Teme* at St Laurence's Church in Ludlow.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-e-housman] These lectures are listed by date of delivery, with date of first publication given separately if different.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The **A-level** (**Advanced Level**) is a main school leaving qualification of the General Certificate of Education in England, Wales, Northern Ireland, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It is available as an alternative qualification in other countries, where it is similarly known as an A-Level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Students generally study for A-levels over a two-year period.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] For much of their history, A-levels have been examined by written exams taken at the end of these two years.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2015, Ofqual decided to change back to a terminal approach where students sit all examinations at the end of the second year.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] AS is still offered, but as a separate qualification; AS grades no longer count towards a subsequent A-level in England.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Most students study three or four A-level subjects simultaneously during the two post-16 years (ages 16–18) in a secondary school, in a sixth form college, in a further and higher education college, or in a tertiary college, as part of their further education.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In the UK, some schools and colleges offer one-year A Level retake programmes for students who wish to improve their grades.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels were introduced in 1951 as a standardised school-leaving qualification, replacing the Higher School Certificate.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The examinations were taken on a subject-by-subject basis, the subjects being chosen according to the strengths and interests of the student.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] This encouraged specialization and in-depth study of three to four subjects.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] At first, A-levels were graded as simply distinction, pass or fail (although students were given an indication of their marks, to the nearest 5%).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Candidates obtaining a distinction originally had the option to sit a scholarship level paper on the same material, to attempt to win one of 400 national scholarships.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The scholarship level was renamed the S-Level in 1963.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Quite soon, rising numbers of students taking the A-level examinations required more differentiation of achievement below the S-Level standard.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Grades were therefore introduced, with recommendations by the Secondary School Examinations Council (SSEC) of approximate proportions of pupils for each grade.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The O grade was equivalent to a GCE Ordinary Level pass which indicated a performance equivalent to the lowest pass grade at Ordinary Level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Over time, the validity of this system was questioned because, rather than reflecting a standard, norm referencing simply maintained a specific proportion of candidates at each grade, which in small cohorts was subject to statistical fluctuations in standards.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In 1984, the government's Secondary Examinations Council decided to replace the norm referencing with criterion referencing: grades would in future be awarded on examiner judgement thus eliminating a possible inadequacy of the existing scheme.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The criterion referencing scheme came into effect for the summer 1987 exams as the system set examiners specific criteria for the awarding of B and E grades to candidates, and then divided out the other grades according to fixed percentages.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Rather than awarding an Ordinary Level for the lowest pass, a new "N" (for Nearly passed) was introduced.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Criticisms of A-level grading continued, and when Curriculum 2000 was introduced, the decision was made to have specific criteria for each grade, and the 'N' grade was abolished.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In 1989, Advanced Supplementary (AS) awards were introduced; they were intended to broaden the subjects a pupil studied post 16, and were to complement rather than be part of a pupil's A-level studies.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] AS-Levels were generally taken over two years, and in a subject the pupil was not studying at A-Level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Each AS level contained half the content of an A-Level, and at the same level of difficulty.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Initially, a student might study three subjects at A-Level and one at AS-Level, or often even four subjects at A-Level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] However, due to decreasing public spending on education over time, a growing number of schools and sixth form colleges would now arrange for their pupils to study for three A-Levels instead of four.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels evolved gradually from a two-year linear course with an exam at the end, to a modular course, between the late 1980s and 2000.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] By the year 2000 there was a strong educational reason to standardise the exam and offer greater breadth to students through modules and there was also a pragmatic case based on the inefficiency of linear courses where up to 30% of students were failing to complete or pass.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Curriculum 2000 was introduced in September 2000, with the first new examinations taken in January and June of the following year.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The Curriculum 2000 reforms also replaced the S-Level extension paper with the Advanced Extension Award.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The Conservative Party under Prime Minister David Cameron initiated reforms for A-levels to change from modular to the current linear structure.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] British Examination Boards (Edexcel, AQA and OCR) regulated and accredited by the government of the United Kingdom responded to the government's reform announcements by modifying specifications of several A-level subjects.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] On 18 March 2020, A-level examinations were cancelled in order to curtail the spread of COVID-19 in the 2019–2020 coronavirus pandemic.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The A-level and AS-level qualifications would instead be awarded based upon a mix of teacher assessment and informal "mock" exams taken earlier in the school year.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] On 6 January 2021, Secretary of State for Education Gavin Williamson confirmed that the 2020/21 series of A-levels would also be cancelled, pending further arrangements by Ofqual and the Department for Education.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Prior to the 2015 government reforms of the A-level system, A-levels had (since the Curriculum 2000 reforms) consisted of two equally weighted parts: AS (Advanced Subsidiary) Level, usually assessed in the first year of study, and "A2 Level", usually assessed in the second year of study.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It was typical for an AS course to comprise two or three modules, with the A2 half of the course comprising two or three modules, for a total of four or six modules.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The modules within each part may have been equally weighted, or be of varying weights.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Modules were either assessed by externally marked papers, or by school-assessed, externally moderated coursework.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Following the reforms, A-Levels and AS-Levels have been decoupled, with AS-Level results no longer counting towards the A-Level qualification.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The AS-Level consists of the first half of the A-Level course, and can be taught alongside the first year of the full A-Level course.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Grades are determined by adding up the mark for each component (which is sometimes weighted) and applying a grade boundary.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A wide variety of subjects are offered at A-level by the five exam boards.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Although exam boards often alter their curricula, this table shows the majority of subjects which are consistently available for study.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The number of A-level exams taken by students can vary.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A typical route is to study four subjects at AS level and then drop down to three at A2 level, although some students continue with their fourth subject.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Three is usually the minimum number of A-levels required for university entrance, with some universities specifying the need for a fourth AS subject.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] There is no limit set on the number of A-levels one can study, and a number of students take five or more A-levels.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It is permissible to take A-levels in languages one already speaks fluently, or courses with overlapping content, even if not always fully recognized by universities.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] There are many options that are in place for students to choose to do coursework.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Those who do not reach the minimum standard required for a grade E receive the non-grade **U** (ungraded/unclassified), and those who fail to complete any of the subject's components will receive an **X**.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The process to decide these grades for modular A-levels involves the uniform mark scheme (UMS).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Under this scheme, four-module A-levels have a maximum mark of 400 UMS (or 200 UMS each for AS and A2), and six-module A-levels have a maximum mark of 600 (or 300 UMS each for AS and A2).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The maximum UMS within AS and A2 may be split unequally between each modules.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] For example, a Physics AS may have two exam modules worth 90 UMS and 150 UMS, and a coursework module worth 60 UMS.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The 'raw marks' i.e. actual score received on a test may differ from UMS awarded.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] On each assignment, the correspondence of raw marks to UMS is decided by setting grade boundaries, a process which involves consultation by subject experts and consideration of statistics, aiming to keep standards for each grade the same year on year.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Achieving less than 40% results in a U (unclassified).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] For passing grades, 40% corresponds to an E grade, 50% a D, 60% a C, 70% a B, and 80% an A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The A* grade was introduced in 2010 and is awarded to candidates who average 80% UMS across all modules, with a score over 90% UMS in all A2 modules.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In Mathematics, which comprises six 100 UMS modules, only the C3 and C4 modules count towards this requirement.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In Further Mathematics and Additional Further Mathematics, where more than three A2 modules can be taken, the three best-scoring A2 modules count.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Recent research and the corresponding findings have shown that over a time span of several years students from Northern Ireland outperformed students from England and Wales in A-level examinations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] According to UCAS and HKEAA, the Hong Kong A-level examination has historically been benchmarked against the UK A-levels.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In general, a UK A grade is broadly equivalent to a Hong Kong A-C grade.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] This conclusion is based mainly on the percentage of pupils achieving the respective grades in respective exams.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In the UK, on average 25% of participants of each subject achieved an A grade every year, compared to the 25% A-C rate in Hong Kong – A(4%), A-B (10%), A-C (25%).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] According to the BBC, the percentage of students achieving an A* is about 8–10%, which essentially lies within the A-B range of their Hong Kong counterparts in respective subjects.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In the United States of America the high school diploma is the qualification generally required for entry into colleges and universities.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Students are usually evaluated and granted admission to US higher education institutions based on a combination of school marks, via a transcript from their high school, and a college entrance exam, most commonly the SAT or ACT.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In the United Kingdom, the high school diploma is considered to be at the level of the General Certificate of Secondary Education (GCSE), which is awarded at Year 11.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] For college and university admissions, the high school diploma may be accepted in lieu of the GCSE if an average grade of C is obtained in subjects with a GCSE counterpart.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] As the more academically rigorous A-levels awarded at Year 13 are expected for university admission, the high school diploma alone is generally not considered to meet university requirements.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] College Entrance Examination Board (CEEB) tests, such as the SAT, SAT Subject Tests, or the ACT, may also be considered.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service (UCAS) recommends that in addition to a high school diploma, grades of 3 or above in at least two, or ideally three, Advanced Placement exams may be considered as meeting general entry requirements for admission.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Access arrangements must be approved by the exam board concerned.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] There are others available, but these are the most commonly used.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A-level examinations in the UK are currently administered through 5 examination boards: AQA, OCR, Edexcel (London Examinations), WJEC/Eduqas and CCEA.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The present 5 can trace their roots via a series of mergers or acquisitions to one or more of the originally 9 GCE Examination boards.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Additionally, there are four examination boards offering A-level qualifications internationally: OxfordAQA, Edexcel, Learning Resource Network (LRN) and the CIE.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] OCR and CIE are both branches of the parent organisation, Cambridge Assessment.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] OxfordAQA is a partnership between AQA and Oxford University Press.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In the UK it is customary for schools to register with multiple examination boards and to "mix and match" A-levels to get a combined curriculum that fits the school profile.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The exam boards finance themselves through the fees charged to the schools for administering the examination.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In addition to the centre registration fee, A-level Mathematics will raise £120.00 per student, while Biology, Physics and Chemistry £90.00 per subject and languages such as Spanish, French and German £100.00 or £201.15 depending on the syllabus.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels are usually studied by students in Sixth Form, which refers to the last two years of secondary education in England, Wales and Northern Ireland, taken at ages 16–18.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Some secondary schools have their own Sixth Form, which admits students from lower year groups, but will often accept external applications.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] There are also many specialist Sixth Form and Further Education Colleges which admit from feeder schools across a large geographic area.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Admission to A-level programmes is at the discretion of providers, and usually depends on GCSE grades.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A typical requirement would be 5 A*-C grades at GCSE, although requirements can be higher, particularly for independent schools and grammar schools.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A-levels are offered as an alternate qualification by a small number of educational institutions in Scotland, in place of the standard Scottish Higher, and the Advanced Higher levels of the Scottish Qualifications Certificate.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The schools that offer A-levels are mainly private fee-paying schools particularly for students wishing to attend university in England.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Many international schools choose to use the British system for their wide recognition.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Furthermore, students may choose to sit the papers of British examination bodies at education centres around the world, such as those belonging to the British Council.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] According to the British Council, A-levels are similar to the American Advanced Placement courses which are themselves equivalent to first-year courses of America's four-year bachelor's degrees.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A-level students often apply to universities before they have taken their final exams, with applications administered centrally through UCAS.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] British universities (including Scottish universities, which receive many applicants taking A-levels) consider GCSEs, AS-level results, predicted A-level results, and extracurricular accomplishments when deciding whether applicants should be made an offer through UCAS.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] These offers may be 'unconditional', guaranteeing a place regardless of performance in A2 examinations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Far more often, the offers are conditional on A-level grades, and become void should the student fail to achieve the marks expected by the university (for example, conditional offer of three A-levels at grades B-B-C).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Universities may specify which subjects they wish these grades to be in (for example, conditional offer of grades A-A-B with a grade A in Mathematics).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The offer may include additional requirements, such as attaining a particular grade in the Sixth Term Examination Paper.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The university is obliged to accept the candidate if the conditions are met, but is not obliged to reject a candidate who misses the requirements.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Leniency may in particular be shown if the candidate narrowly misses grades.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A-level grades are also sometimes converted into numerical scores, typically UCAS tariff scores.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Under the new UCAS system starting in 2017, an A* grade at A-level is worth 56 points, while an A is worth 48, a B is worth 40, a C is worth 32, a D is 24, and a E is worth 16; so a university may instead demand that an applicant achieve 112 points, instead of the equivalent offer of B-B-C.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] This allows greater flexibility to students, as 112 points could also, for example, be achieved through the combination A-B-D, which would not have met the requirements of a B-B-C offer because of the D grade.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Depending on the specific offer made, a combination of more than 3 subjects (typically 4 or 5) with lower grades, or points from non-academic input such as higher level music grades or a Key Skills course, may also be accepted by the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The text of the offer determines whether this flexibility is available – "112 UCAS Points" likely would, while "112 UCAS Points from three A-level subjects" would not.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] There are currently three examination boards which provide an international variant of the United Kingdom A-level examinations to international students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] These are Cambridge International Examinations (CIE), Edexcel and OxfordAQA.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] 2020-21 due to COVID-19 grades were teacher awarded, rather than examined.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The most common criticism of the A-level system is an accusation of grade inflation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The press have noted the steady rise in average grades for several consecutive years and drawn the conclusion that A-levels are becoming consistently easier.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A 2007 report by Robert Coe compared students' scores in the ALIS ability test with equivalent grades achieved in A-level exams over a period of approximately 20 years; he found that students of similar ability were achieving on average about 2 grades higher than in the past.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In the case of maths it was nearer to 3.5 grades higher.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The government and teaching bodies maintain that the improved grades represent higher levels of achievement due to improved and more experienced teaching methods, but some educationalists and journalists argue that the change is due to grade inflation and the examinations getting easier.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It has also been suggested that government pressure on schools to achieve high examination results has led them to coach students to pass the examination rather than understand the subject.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2000, the A-level system was changed to examine students at the end of each of the two years of A-level study, rather than only at the end of the two years.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The results of the first year's exam (AS-level) allowed students to drop subjects they find difficult after one year and to retake AS examinations to achieve a higher grade at that level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The availability to resit the AS paper, with the best mark contributing to the full A level, has improved results of the A level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Some believe that students are tending to select easier subjects in order to achieve higher grades.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Universities in Britain have complained that the increasing number of A grades awarded makes it hard to distinguish between students at the upper end of the ability spectrum.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Many universities administer their own entrance tests such as the BMAT and LNAT for specific courses, or conduct interviews to select applicants.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2005, the head of admissions at the University of Cambridge outlined changes he believed should be made to the current system, particularly the use of the Advanced Extension Awards, a more challenging qualification based on the more advanced content of the A-level syllabus.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] More universities have wanted to see applicants' individual module results to see how comfortably they have achieved their result due to fears that the A-level might not offer an accurate test of ability, or that it is a good prediction of future academic success.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2002, allegations that students had been given lower marks than they deserved in order to fix overall results and make the pass rate seem lower than it had been in previous years were raised.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The Tomlinson Inquiry was set up to ascertain whether this was an underhand way to disprove that A-levels were becoming too easy.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] As a result, some papers were re-marked but only 1,220 A-level and 733 AS-level students saw an improvement to their results.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] To replace the cancelled summer 2020 examination series (owing to concerns over the spread of COVID-19), grades were awarded using *centre-assessed grades* and rankings.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] These were initially moderated by Ofqual but, owing to numerous problems, candidates' final grades reverted to those supplied by centres.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] This resulted in significant grade inflation, with initial calculations showing around 37.7% of candidates gaining a grade A or A*, compared with 25.2% in 2019.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In response to concerns shown by employers and universities that it was not possible to distinguish exceptional candidates among the large number of students achieving A grades, and in order to mirror GCSE standards, a higher "super A" grade (like the A* grade at GCSE) was proposed in 2004.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] For modular A2 exams sat from 2010 onwards, the highest A-level grade is A*, requiring an A grade overall and 90% overall average UMS in A2 papers.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The 2004 reform of the Mathematics syllabus, following calls that it was too hard, attracted criticism.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In the change, content consisting of three modules (Pure 1–3) was spread to four modules (Core 1–4).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It was alleged that this made the course easier as students did less work for the same qualifications.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Further reforms in 2006 to make the Mathematics syllabus more popular were met with mixed opinions.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Supporters cited it would reverse the downward trend in students taking the subject whilst others were concerned that the subject was "still incredibly difficult".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Examples of concerns were those raised in 2009 by Sir Mike Rake, Chairman of BT Group, Sir Terry Leahy, Chairman of Tesco and by Sir Christopher Gent, Chairman of GlaxoSmithKline.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Some schools have also moved to offering the Cambridge Pre-U as an alternative to A-levels and with higher tariffs.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] With increased modularisation of subjects, the amount of time that young adults are spending being examined in the UK has risen considerably.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It was estimated in a report by educationalists that by the age of 19 children will have spent an entire year of their school education being assessed.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] As a result of such criticisms about the "burden of assessment", since candidates have taken four papers for most A-levels, instead of six as in the past.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] This means that there are two modules for AS and two more for A2 for the majority of A-levels.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] However, this will not be the case for all A-levels: Biology, Human Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Electronics, Geology, Music, Welsh and Science will continue with six units, three units for AS and A2 respectively, and 600 UMS for the A-level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Mathematics (including Further Mathematics, Additional Further Mathematics, Statistics, and the Use of Mathematics AS), will not change structurally in the modular reform; it will stay on 600 UMS (300 UMS for AS), but it will include the new A* grade and the 'Stretch and Challenge' provision.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Also, Bengali, Modern Hebrew, Punjabi, Polish, Arabic, Japanese, Modern Greek, Biblical Hebrew, Dutch, Gujarati, Persian, Portuguese, and Turkish will remain at two units, one for AS and one for A2.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] However, they will move to 200 UMS for A-level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Chinese will also move to 200 UMS, but instead of two units, it will move to three units: AS will have two units, A2 will have one.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It is the first A-level to have an odd number of units since Curriculum 2000.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Cambridge University has warned that it is extremely unlikely that it will accept applicants who are taking two or more supposedly 'softer' A-level subjects out of 3.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It has outlined a list of subjects it considers to be 'unsuitable', which includes Accounting, Design and Technology, Film Studies, Information and Communication Technology, Media Studies, Photography, and Sports studies.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] As a result of dislike of the modular system, many schools now offer the alternative International Baccalaureate Diploma qualification.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The course offers more subjects, extracurricular activity, a philosophical epistemological component known as "Theory of Knowledge", as well as the requirement of an extended essay on any subject of a candidate's choice.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Unlike the current AS/A2 system, the International Baccalaureate is not based on a modular system.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The Diploma Programme, administered by the International Baccalaureate, is a recognised pre-university educational programme.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Former British Prime Minister Tony Blair suggested in 2013 that one state school in every county should offer the International Baccalaureate Diploma Programme as an alternative to A-levels.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Maths, Chemistry, or Biology), a language subject (e.g.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] English Language, English Literature, French, German, Spanish), and a "creative" subject (e.g.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Art Studies)—in many cases students choose three closely linked subjects—for example, Mathematics, Physics and Chemistry or Sociology, Psychology, and Politics.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] This is in part due to university entrance requirements, which, for degree programs such as medicine, may require three related A-level subjects, but non-traditional combinations are becoming more common ("British Council Australia Education UK").
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Thus, while the purpose of Curriculum 2000 was to encourage students to undertake contrasting subjects, to broaden their 'skill-base', there is a tendency to pursue similar disciplines.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] However, others disagree, arguing that the additional AS-level(s) studied would already have provided more breadth compared with the old system.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Students applying to universities before receiving their A-level results typically do so on the basis of predicted grades, which are issued by schools and colleges.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A student's predicted grades usually depend on their GCSE results, performance throughout the course, performance in tests and mock examinations, or a combination of these factors.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A possible reformation would be something called the post-qualifications applications system (PQA), where applicants apply to university after they receive their results.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It has been argued that this would be fairer to applicants, especially those from lower-income families whose results were thought to be under-predicted.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] However, a more recent UCAS report shows that although the reliability of predicted grades declines in step with family income, this can still lead to an over-prediction effect for lower income groups.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Just 45% of predicted grades are accurate – 47% are over-predictions and 9% under-predictions.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] A recent UCAS consultation rejected the implementation of PQA following opposition from universities, schools and awarding bodies.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] In 2020 the A-level system was challenged by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Ofqual advised that the 2020 A-level exams should be cancelled, students be given a completion certificate, and universities widen the intake relying on a higher drop-out.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] The government intervened and grades were to be awarded using an algorithm.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] There was a public outcry, explained Roger Taylor the former chair of Ofqual who resigned.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] It was a “colossal error of judgment”: awarding grades calculated by algorithm was not acceptable to the public.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Instead the final grades were awarded by teacher assessment, a system that was repeated in 2021.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Taylor explained the algorithm was robust, it was the way it was being used that caused the problem: that was down to human decisions.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-level-united-kingdom] Researchers from the London School of Economics and University College London researchers showed that teacher assessment gave a 15% advantage to students with graduate parents.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] They were introduced in England, Wales and Northern Ireland in 1951 to replace the Higher School Certificate.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The A-level permits students to have potential access to a chosen university they applied to with UCAS points.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] They could be accepted into it should they meet the requirements of the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] A number of Commonwealth countries have developed qualifications with the same name as and a similar format to the British A-levels.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Obtaining an A-level, or equivalent qualifications, is generally required across the board for university entrance, with universities granting offers based on grades achieved.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] A-levels are typically worked towards over two years.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Normally, students take three or four A-level courses in their first year of sixth form, and most taking four cut back to three in their second year.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] This is because university offers are normally based on three A-level grades, and taking a fourth can have an impact on grades.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Unlike other level-3 qualifications, such as the International Baccalaureate, A-levels have no specific subject requirements, so students have the opportunity to combine any subjects they wish to take.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] However, students normally pick their courses based on the degree they wish to pursue at university: most degrees require specific A-levels for entry.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The second part is known as an A2 or A2-level, which is generally more in-depth and academically rigorous than the AS.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The AS and A2 marks are combined for a full A-level award.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The A2-level is not a qualification on its own and must be accompanied by an AS-level in the same subject for certification.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] A-level exams are a matriculation examination and can be compared to *matura*, the *Abitur*, the *Baccalauréat* or the Bagrut certificate.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Several countries use A-levels as a school-leaving qualification.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] However, A levels are mainly taken in the UK.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The A-levels taken by students in other countries may differ from the A-levels taken in the United Kingdom.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Many schools in countries world-wide offer A-Levels through international cross-border exam boards, which include Cambridge International Education (CIE), Pearson Edexcel, Learning Resource Network (LRN) and OxfordAQA.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] A-levels are a college or sixth form leaving qualification offered in England, Wales, and Northern Ireland.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In Scotland, A-levels are also offered by some schools as an alternative school-leaving qualification in place of the Scottish Advanced Higher.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Oxford AQA, Edexcel, Cambridge International Education (CIE), and Learning Resource Network (LRN) also offer international versions of the British A-levels in the United Kingdom and worldwide.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The British variant of A/AS-levels is also taken in many Commonwealth and former Commonwealth countries, as well as in examination centers worldwide.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] British international schools in foreign countries generally offer the British A-levels as offered through Edexcel or Cambridge International Examinations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] At select examination centers, the British A-level exams may also be available to private candidates.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In Bangladesh, the GCE AS and A-level are offered by Cambridge International Education (CIE) and Pearson Edexcel after completion of IGCSE (CIE or Pearson Edexcel) or Cambridge O-Level, and is conducted by the British Council.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] GCE Advanced Level qualifications are offered by some of the private, public, and international schools as an alternative to HSC (Higher Secondary School Certificate) offered by the Government Board of Education.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] It has become a popular choice among students, but due to financial implications, its reach is limited to the middle and upper classes in major cities such as Dhaka and Chittagong.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In Brunei, the A-level qualification is offered, with examinations conducted by Cambridge International Education (CIE).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Some subjects are unique to Brunei or have a format, curriculum, or syllabus that is unique to Brunei.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The Advanced Level of Cameroon is based on the Cambridge International Education and similarly, conducted by the government of Cameroon in collaboration with Cambridge University.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] All the courses taken are related to what the candidate is willing to pursue a career in university and these courses are on a recognizable international standard for university entrance; as they are major relevant courses.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The British A-level qualifications such as GCE A-level and International A-level are widely accepted in Hong Kong as an alternative to the Hong Kong Diploma of Secondary Education for both admission and employment purposes.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] It is one of the most popular qualifications used for university admission via the non-JUPAS channel.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] For example, average non-JUPAS offers from the Hong Kong University of Science and Technology require one to three A*s (the mid-50% range).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Since the introduction of the high distinction grade (A*) in 2010, the British A-level examination has regained its power to differentiate the very top levels of ability.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] According to the British Department for Education, in the academic year 2014/15, approximately 7.3%, 2.7%, 1.0%, and 0.3% of all the candidates from the GCSE cohort (548,480) achieved one to four A*s or a better result in the GCE A-level examination.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] This percentile rank is one important input for equating the levels in both examinations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] On the sole basis of percentile ranks and the grade statistics from HKEAA in 2017, a score of 29/35 from the best five subjects in Hong Kong Diploma of Secondary Education is comparable to 1A*2A in the best three British A-levels, 32/35 to 2A*1A, 33/35 to 3A* and 34/35 to 4A*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Relevant authorities such as the Hong Kong Examination and Assessment Authority (HKEAA) and UCAS also sought to connect the results from both exam systems to open doors for the holders of these qualifications who wish to study locally or overseas.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Officially, the top distinction levels, A* in A-level and 5** in HKDSE, are currently recognized as broadly equivalent.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In India, Cambridge International Education (CIE), and Learning Resource Network (LRN) GCE Advanced Level qualifications are offered at private and international schools as an alternative to the conventional Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The International A-Level qualifications are offered in some private schools and international schools which teaching medium is English and adopt IAL curriculum.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Students in Macau can take the Cambridge International Education (CIE) or Edexcel International A-Level offered at their school.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] It is one of the most popular qualifications for the students who want to pursue their university study in UK, Hong Kong, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] International Advanced Level qualification is also accepted by Macau local universities for applying for direct admission, the applicants with IAL qualification are not required to take the Joint Admission Examination for Macao Four Higher Education Institutions.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In Malaysia, the A-level qualification is offered, with examinations conducted by Cambridge International Education (CIE) and Learning Resource Network.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Some subjects are unique to Malaysia or have a format, curriculum, or syllabus that is unique to Malaysia.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] For instance, there are two types of A-level in Malaysia, Cambridge A-level (administered by Cambridge International Examinations) and Edexcel International Advanced Level (administered by Pearson Edexcel).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Some exam papers offered, such as French, are customized to support the national educational standards.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Additionally, International A-level qualifications from Edexcel are available, for which exams may be registered through the Mauritius Examinations Syndicate.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In Nepal, A-level offered from Cambridge International Education (CIE) is the most popular and is presented by several public, private, and international institutions as an alternative to the National Examination Board's 10+2 curriculum.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] A-level has become a popular choice for many students in Nepal.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Besides A-level, International Baccalaureate and Advanced Placement are also offered at this level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Nepali students generally appear for 4 subjects at A-level and 5 at AS-level.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] A-levels are offered in Pakistan by governmental and private institutions, along with International Baccalaureate and other international examinations like the Advanced Placement though A levels is by far the most popular.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Examinations are handled by international British boards and the program is equivalent to Higher Secondary School Certificate.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Cram Schools are established all around the country which prepares the students to take the examinations as private candidates.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In Seychelles, the A-level qualification is offered, with examinations conducted by Cambridge International Education (CIE).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Some subjects are unique to Seychelles or have a format, curriculum, or syllabus that is unique to Seychelles.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In Singapore, H1/H2/H3 level qualifications are awarded upon successful completion of examinations jointly administered by Singapore Ministry of Education (MOE), Singapore Examinations and Assessment Board (SEAB) and Cambridge International Education (CIE).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In Sri Lanka, A-level qualifications are offered by governmental and non-governmental schools (Private Schools).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The qualifications are awarded upon successful completion of examinations called Local A-levels while most of the private schools award them upon London A-levels.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Local GCE Advanced Level qualifications are offered by the Department of Examinations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Passing A-levels is a major requirement for applying to local universities and for private universities in Sri Lanka.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In the recent past, Universities in Sri Lanka have given the opportunity to apply for their foundation courses which only require O-level (Ordinary Level) results.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] A-level is an education structure after the completion of 11 years of Universal Primary Education (UPE).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Universal Primary Education consists of two levels, the primary school level of seven years and ordinarily secondary level, of four years.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Students are then required to sit for the National Examination which is done on a specific month in a certain year.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The exams are done throughout the country on the same date provided by the examination board.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Examinations will depend on the cluster and core subjects in which a student shall take.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] There are three major clusters, namely science, business, and liberal arts plus core subjects of which are seven in total or more.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Students who will then pass according to the National Examination Standards shall be selected to join Advanced Secondary Education and are selected according to the subjects they passed the most and by their will to pursue certain subjects.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] There are only three core subjects to study in Advanced Level and one or more optional subjects to sit for the Advanced Certificate of Secondary Education Examination (ACSEE).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Then students are awarded Advanced Certificate of Secondary Education only if they have passed.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The pass marks are arranged according to grades and the grades will determine whether a student will qualify to join tertiary education.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] A-level education is a two years education which is offered by the government and non-government schools.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In Uganda, a Uganda Advanced Certificate of Education is awarded to students who have passed their national examinations that are set and marked by the Uganda National Examination Board (UNEB).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] It is among the requirements for one to join a university in Uganda.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The advanced level takes two years for one to complete.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Some international schools in Uganda also offer A-level courses from Cambridge and Edexcel.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The GCE Advanced Level qualification is offered by the Zimbabwe School Examinations Council (ZIMSEC).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Before, this qualification was jointly offered by Cambridge International Education and the Council in Zimbabwe.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Although exam boards often alter their curricula, this table shows the majority of subjects that are consistently available for study.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Between 2015 and 2018 (first assessment Summer 2017), A-levels in England were reformed, transitioning from a modular to linear structure (initially across 13 subjects).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] This means all A-level exams are taken in one sitting as a set of terminal exams (three exams for the majority of subjects), and there is no coursework set for many subjects.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] For A-levels that retain a coursework element, the percentage of the final grade determined by coursework has been reduced.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] An example of this can be seen in Edexcel's new English Literature A-level, reformed in 2015, which reduces the amount of coursework to 20% (from 40% in the old modular specification).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] A-levels are no longer separated into units, and students must resit all of their exams if they wish to resit the qualification.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] While these reforms were expected to be complete for first teaching in 2017, this was extended to 2018 to include the reforms of less common languages such as Modern Hebrew and Bengali.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The AS-level is now a separate qualification and is not required for an A-level award, although it still encompasses the first year of the full A-level content.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] However, unlike AS-levels in the old modular courses, they are now worth only 40% as many UCAS points as a full A-level (from 50% in the modular courses), as content from the second year of A-level is considered more academically challenging than that of the first year.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] As these reforms took place in stages, many students took a combination of modular and linear courses before all reforms were complete, with AS-levels still being part of an A-level in older modular courses.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] These reforms look to combat grade inflation, where the proportion of students achieving the highest grades increases year upon year, causing the value of those grades to be eroded.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The modular system has also been criticised for nurturing a 'resit culture', while new linear courses give no opportunity to resit individual units.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Controversially, some A-level course subjects have been abolished since 2017 as part of these reforms.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] These include archaeology, anthropology, creative writing, general studies, and home economics.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Many universities criticised the scrapping of exams taken at the end of AS-level, which used to be worth 50% of the overall A-level grade.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] This is because the universities used the grades achieved at AS-level (available to universities after a student applies during the second year of A-levels) as an indication of a student's ability and thus whether to give said student an offer.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Opposition to these reforms in Wales and Northern Ireland has resulted in maintaining the modular structure of their qualification.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In September 2023, it was announced by Prime Minister Rishi Sunak that the A-level would be scrapped in England and merged with T-levels to form the Advanced British Standard, however this was cancelled by the Labour government after the 2024 general election.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] In 2002, schools in the Caribbean began to move away from the GCE Advanced Level to the CXC CAPE examinations, making them a de facto university entrance examination.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] Some universities also require applicants to take separate entrance examinations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-levels] The International Baccalaureate and European Baccalaureate are also accepted.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] After attending the University of Cambridge, she married in 1959 and moved to Durham.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] It was during Byatt's time at university that she began working on her first two novels, subsequently published by Chatto & Windus as *Shadow of a Sun* (1964; reprinted in 1991 with its originally intended title, *The Shadow of the Sun*) and *The Game* (1967).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt took a teaching job in 1972 to help pay for the education of her son.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] In the same week she accepted the teaching job, a drunk driver killed her son as he walked home from school.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt spent a symbolic 11 years teaching, then began full-time writing in 1983.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] *The Virgin in the Garden* (1978) was the first of *The Quartet*, a tetralogy of novels that continued with *Still Life* (1985), *Babel Tower* (1996) and *A Whistling Woman* (2002).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt's novel *Possession: A Romance* received the 1990 Booker Prize, while her short story collection *The Djinn in the Nightingale's Eye* (1994) received the 1995 Aga Khan Prize for Fiction.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Her novel *The Children's Book* was shortlisted for the 2009 Booker Prize and won the 2010 James Tait Black Memorial Prize.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Her critical work includes two studies of Dame Iris Murdoch (who was a friend and mentor), *Degrees of Freedom: The Early Novels of Iris Murdoch* (1965) and *Iris Murdoch: A Critical Study* (1976).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Her other critical studies include *Wordsworth and Coleridge in Their Time* (1970) and *Portraits in Fiction* (2001).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt was awarded the Shakespeare Prize in 2002, the Erasmus Prize in 2016, the Park Kyong-ni Prize in 2017 and the Hans Christian Andersen Literature Award in 2018.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She was mentioned as a candidate for the Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Antonia Susan Drabble was born in Sheffield, England, on 24 August 1936, as the eldest child of John Frederick Drabble, QC, later a County Court judge, and Kathleen Bloor, a scholar of Browning.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Her sister is the novelist Margaret Drabble.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] The Drabble father participated in the placement of Jewish refugees in Sheffield during the 1930s.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Her mother was a Shavian and her father was a Quaker.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] As a result of the bombing of Sheffield during the Second World War the family moved to York.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt was educated at two independent boarding schools, Sheffield High School and The Mount School, a Quaker boarding school at York.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] An unhappy child, Byatt did not enjoy boarding school, citing her need to be alone and her difficulty in making friends.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Severe asthma often kept her in bed where reading became an escape from a difficult household.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She attended Newnham College, Cambridge, Bryn Mawr College (in the United States), and Somerville College, Oxford.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Having studied French, German, Latin and English at school, she later studied Italian while attending Cambridge so that she could read Dante.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt lectured in the Department of Extra-Mural Studies of the University of London (1962–71), the Central School of Art and Design and from 1972 to 1983 at University College London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt married Ian Charles Rayner Byatt in 1959 and moved to Durham.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] They had a daughter together, as well as a son, Charles, who was killed by a drunk-driver at the age of 11 while walking home from school.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She spoke of her son's death and its influence on her lecturing and subsequent career after publishing *The Children's Book*, in which the image of a dead child features.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She came to regard her academic career symbolically.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Later that year, Byatt married Peter Duffy, and they had two daughters.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt's relationship with her sister Margaret Drabble was sometimes strained due to the presence of autobiographical elements in both their writing.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She enjoyed watching snooker, tennis, and football.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt lived primarily in Putney, and died at home on 16 November 2023, at the age of 87.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt was influenced by Henry James and George Eliot as well as Emily Dickinson, T.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Eliot, Samuel Taylor Coleridge, Tennyson and Robert Browning, in merging realism and naturalism with fantasy.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She was not an admirer of the Brontë family, nor did she like Christina Rossetti.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She knew Jane Austen's work "off by heart" before her teens.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] In her books, Byatt alluded to, and built upon, themes from Romantic and Victorian literature.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She cited art historian John Gage's book on the theory of colour as one of her favourite books to reread.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt wrote a lot while attending boarding school but had most of it burnt before she left.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She left it in a drawer when she was finished.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] After departing Cambridge, she spent one year as a postgraduate student in the United States and began her second novel, *The Game*, continuing to write it at Oxford when she returned to England.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] After getting married in 1959 and moving to Durham, she left *The Game* aside and resumed work on her earlier novel.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She sent it to literary critic John Beer, whom she had befriended while at Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Beer sent Byatt's novel to the independent book publishing company Chatto & Windus.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] From there Cecil Day-Lewis wrote her a response and invited her to lunch at The Athenaeum.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] The family theme is continued in *The Quartet*, Byatt's tetralogy of novels, which begins with *The Virgin in the Garden* (1978) and continues with *Still Life* (1985), *Babel Tower* (1996) and *A Whistling Woman* (2002).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Lawrence, particularly *The Rainbow* and *Women in Love*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] The family portrayed in the quartet are from Yorkshire.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt said the idea for *The Virgin in the Garden* came in part from an extramural class she taught in which she had read Tolstoy and Dostoevsky and in part from her time living in Durham in 1961, the year in which her son was born.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] The book was an attempt to understand what could be achieved if *Middlemarch* were written in the middle of the twentieth century.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt's book features a powerful death scene, which she invented in 1961 (inspired by Byatt's reading of Angus Wilson's book *The Middle Age of Mrs Eliot* and the accident in its opening), a death scene that has drawn complaints from numerous readers for its vividness.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Describing mid-20th-century Britain, the books follow the life of Frederica Potter, a young intellectual studying at Cambridge at a time when women were heavily outnumbered by men at that university, and then tracing her journey as a divorcée with a young son as he makes a new life in London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt says some of the characters in her fiction represent her "greatest terror which is simple domesticity." Like *Babel Tower*, *A Whistling Woman* touches on the utopian and revolutionary dreams of the 1960s.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Also an accomplished short story writer, Byatt's first published collection was *Sugar and Other Stories* (1987).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] *The Matisse Stories* (1993) features three pieces, each describing a painting by the eponymous painter; each is the tale of an initially smaller crisis that shows the long-present unravelling in the protagonists' lives.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] *The Djinn in the Nightingale's Eye*, published in 1994, is a collection of fairy tales.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt's other short story collections are *Elementals: Stories of Fire and Ice*, published in 1998, and *Little Black Book of Stories*, published in 2003.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Her books reflect a continuous interest in zoology, entomology, geology, and Darwinism among other repeated themes.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She is also interested in linguistics and takes a keen interest in the translation of her books.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt said: "I can't say how important it was to me when Angela Carter said 'I grew up on fairy stories—they're much more important to me than realist narratives'.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] I hadn't had the nerve to think that until she said it, and I owe her a great deal".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Carter, in an earlier (first) meeting with Byatt after a Stevie Smith poetry reading, had dismissed Byatt's work, so this change of heart vindicated Byatt's approach to writing and Byatt readily acknowledged it.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt's novella *Morpho Eugenia* was included in *Angels & Insects* (1992), which was turned into the eponymous 1995 film; that film received an Academy Award for Best Costume Design in 1997.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt's novel *The Biographer's Tale*, published in 2000, she originally intended as a short story titled "The Biography of a Biographer", based on her notion of a biographer's life in a library investigating another person's life.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] This she developed into writing about a character called Phineas G.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Nanson, who is attempting to learn about a biographer for a book he intends to write, but who can only locate fragments of his three unwritten biographies, which are on Galton, Ibsen and Linnaeus.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Phineas Gilbert Nanson is named after an insect and is almost an anagram of Galton, Ibsen and Linnaeus, though Byatt said this was an uncanny coincidence that she did not realise until afterwards.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She wrote at her home in Putney, West London, and at another house in the Cévennes in Southern France, where she spent her summers.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She did not write her fiction on a computer, she did so by hand, though she had deployed a computer for non-fiction articles.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] So what I like to do is to write from about half past twelve, one, through to about four".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] At this point, she said, she would begin reading again.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt wrote two critical studies of Iris Murdoch, who was a friend, mentor and another significant influence on her own writing.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] They were titled *Degrees of Freedom: The Early Novels of Iris Murdoch* (1965) and *Iris Murdoch: A Critical Study* (1976).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt's other critical studies include *Wordsworth and Coleridge in Their Time* (1970).
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] 2001's *Portraits in Fiction* is about painting in novels, and features references to Emile Zola, Marcel Proust and Iris Murdoch; Byatt had earlier touched upon this subject in a 2000 lecture she delivered at the National Portrait Gallery in London.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt had been a public encourager of the new young generation of British writers, including Philip Hensher (*Kitchen Venom*), Robert Irwin (*Exquisite Corpse*), A.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She contrasted some of those preferences with the work of Martin Amis, Julian Barnes, Ian McEwan and Graham Swift—then added, "In fact I admire all four of those writers... they don't only do people's feelings... nevertheless it's become ossified".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Norfolk she described in 2003 as "the best of the young novelists now writing".
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She also spoke of her admiration for American writer Helen DeWitt's book *The Last Samurai*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Hensher, who counts Byatt as a friend, said: "She's very unusual for an English person, in that she's quite suspicious of comedy.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt was a judge on many literary award panels, including the Betty Trask Award, the David Higham Prize for Fiction, the Hawthornden Prize and the Booker.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] She also wrote for the media, including for *The Times Literary Supplement*, British journal *Prospect* and newspapers *The Guardian*, *The Independent* and *The Sunday Times*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt was mentioned as a candidate for the Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] Byatt was appointed Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE) in the 1990 New Year Honours, and was promoted to Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire (DBE), "for services to Literature", in Elizabeth II's 1999 Birthday Honours.
[src:university-of-cambridge/a-s-byatt] The following books form a tetralogy known as *The Quartet*: *The Virgin in the Garden* (1978), *Still Life* (1985), *Babel Tower* (1996) and *A Whistling Woman* (2002).
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The **University of Cambridge** is a collegiate public research university in Cambridge, England.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Founded in 1209, the University of Cambridge is the second-oldest university in the English-speaking world and the world's third-oldest university in continuous operation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university's founding followed the arrival of scholars who left the University of Oxford for Cambridge after a dispute with local townspeople.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The two ancient English universities, although sometimes described as rivals, share many common features and are often jointly referred to as *Oxbridge*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In 1231, 22 years after its founding, the university was recognised with a royal charter, granted by King Henry III.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The University of Cambridge includes 31 semi-autonomous constituent colleges and more than 150 academic departments, faculties, and other institutions organised into six schools.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The largest department is Cambridge University Press and Assessment, which contains the oldest university press in the world, with £1 billion of annual revenue and with 100 million learners.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] All of the colleges are self-governing institutions within the university, managing their own personnel and policies, and all students are required to have a college affiliation within the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Undergraduate teaching at Cambridge is centred on weekly small-group supervisions in the colleges with lectures, seminars, laboratory work, and occasionally further supervision provided by the central university faculties and departments.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university operates eight cultural and scientific museums, including the Fitzwilliam Museum and Cambridge University Botanic Garden.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Cambridge's 116 libraries hold a total of approximately 16 million books, around 9 million of which are in Cambridge University Library, a legal deposit library and one of the world's largest academic libraries.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Its alumni, academics, and affiliates have won 126 Nobel Prizes.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Prior to the founding of the University of Cambridge in 1209, Cambridge and the area surrounding it already had developed a scholarly and ecclesiastical reputation largely due to the intellectual and academic contributions of monks from the nearby Ely Cathedral.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The founding of the university, however, mostly originated with an incident at the University of Oxford during which two Oxford scholars, following the death of a local woman, were hanged by the town's secular authorities.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The local ecclesiastical authorities, who were not consulted, would have traditionally been inclined to pardon scholars in such cases.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] During this time, Oxford's town authorities were in conflict with King John.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Fearing more violence from Oxford townsfolk, University of Oxford scholars began leaving Oxford for more hospitable cities, including Paris, Reading, and Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Enough scholars ultimately took residence in Cambridge to form, along with the many scholars already there, the nucleus for the new university's foundation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] A letter from Pope Gregory IX two years later to the chancellor and the guild of scholars granted the new university *ius non trahi extra*, or the right not to be drawn out, for three years, meaning its members could not be summoned to a court outside of the diocese of Ely.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] After Cambridge was described as a *studium generale* in a letter from Pope Nicholas IV in 1290, and confirmed as such by Pope John XXII's 1318 papal bull, it became common for researchers from other European medieval universities to visit Cambridge to study or give lectures.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The 31 colleges of the present-day University of Cambridge were originally an incidental feature of the university; no college within the University of Cambridge is as old as the university itself.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The colleges within the university were initially endowed fellowships of scholars.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] There were also institutions without endowments, called hostels, which were gradually absorbed by the colleges over the centuries, and they have left some traces, including the naming of Garret Hostel Lane and Garret Hostel Bridge, a street and bridge in Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The University of Cambridge's first college, Peterhouse, was founded in 1284 by Hugh de Balsham, the Bishop of Ely.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Multiple additional colleges were founded during the 14th and 15th centuries, and colleges continued to be established during modern times, though there was a 204-year gap between the founding of Sidney Sussex in 1596 and that of Downing in 1800.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The most recent college to be established is Robinson, which was built in the late 1970s.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Most recently, in March 2010, Homerton College achieved full university college status, making it the university's newest full college.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In medieval times, many colleges were founded so that their members could pray for the souls of the founders.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] University of Cambridge colleges were often associated with chapels or abbeys.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The colleges' focus began to shift in 1536, however, with the dissolution of the monasteries and Henry VIII's order that the university disband the canon law that governed the university's faculty and stop teaching scholastic philosophy.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In response, colleges changed their curricula from canon law to classics, the Bible, and mathematics.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Nearly a century later, the university found itself at the centre of a Protestant schism.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Many nobles, intellectuals, and also commoners saw the Church of England as too similar to the Catholic Church and felt that it was being used by The Crown to usurp the counties' rightful powers.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] East Anglia emerged as the centre of what ultimately became the Puritan movement.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In Cambridge, the Puritan movement was particularly strong at Emmanuel, St Catharine Hall, Sidney Sussex, and Christ's.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] These colleges produced many nonconformist graduates who greatly influenced, by social position or preaching, some 20,000 Puritans who ultimately left England for New England and especially the Massachusetts Bay Colony during the Great Migration decade of the 1630s.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university quickly established itself as a global leader in the study of mathematics.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university's examination in mathematics, known as the Mathematical Tripos, was initially compulsory for all undergraduates studying for the Bachelor of Arts degree, the most common degree first offered at Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] From the time of Isaac Newton in the late 17th century until the mid-19th century, the university maintained an especially strong emphasis on applied mathematics, and especially mathematical physics.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The Cambridge Mathematical Tripos is highly competitive and has helped produce some of the most famous names in British science, including James Clerk Maxwell, Lord Kelvin, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] However, some famous students, such as G.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Hardy, disliked the Tripos system, feeling that students were becoming too focused on accumulating high exam marks at the expense of the subject itself.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Pure mathematics at the University of Cambridge in the 19th century achieved great things, though it largely missed out on substantial developments in French and German mathematics.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] By the early 20th century, however, pure mathematical research at Cambridge reached the highest international standard, thanks largely to G.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Hodge and others helped establish Cambridge as a global leader in geometry in the 1930s.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The Cambridge University Act 1856 formalised the university's organisational structure and introduced the study of many new subjects, including theology, history, and Modern languages.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Resources necessary for new courses in the arts, architecture, and archaeology were donated by Viscount Fitzwilliam of Trinity College, who also founded Fitzwilliam Museum in 1816.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In 1847, Prince Albert was elected the university's chancellor in a close contest with the Earl of Powis.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] As chancellor, Albert reformed university curricula beyond its initial focus on mathematics and classics, adding modern era history and the natural sciences.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Between 1896 and 1902, Downing College sold part of its land to permit the construction of Downing Site, the university's grouping of scientific laboratories for the study of anatomy, genetics, and Earth sciences.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] During this period, the New Museums Site was erected, including the Cavendish Laboratory, which has since moved to West Cambridge, and other departments for chemistry and medicine.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The University of Cambridge began to award PhD degrees in the first third of the 20th century; the first Cambridge PhD in mathematics was awarded in 1924.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university contributed significantly to the Allies' forces in World War I with 13,878 members of the university serving and 2,470 being killed in action during the war.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Teaching, and the fees it earned, nearly came to a halt during World War I, and severe financial difficulties followed.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] As a result, the university received its first systematic state support in 1919, and a Royal commission was appointed in 1920 to recommend that the university (but not its colleges) begin receiving an annual grant.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Following World War II, the university experienced a rapid expansion in applications and enrolment, partly due to the success and popularity gained by many Cambridge scientists.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] This was not without controversies, however.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] For example, Cambridge researchers were accused in 2023 of helping to develop weapon systems for Iran.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The University of Cambridge was one of only two universities to hold parliamentary seats in the Parliament of England and was later one of 19 represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The constituency was created by a Royal charter of 1603 and returned two members of parliament until 1950 when it was abolished by the Representation of the People Act 1948.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The constituency was not a geographical area; rather, its electorate consisted of university graduates.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Before 1918, the franchise was restricted to male graduates with a doctorate or MA degree.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] For the first several centuries of its existence, as was the case broadly in England and the world, the University of Cambridge was only open to male students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Prior to ultimately being permitted admission to the university in 1948, female students were granted the right to take University of Cambridge exams beginning in the late 19th century.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Women were also allowed to study courses, take examinations, and have prior exam results recorded retroactively, dating back to 1881; for a brief period after the turn of the 20th century, this allowed the steamboat ladies to receive *ad eundem* degrees from the University of Dublin.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In 1998, a special graduation ceremony was held in which the women who attended Cambridge before admission was allowed in 1948 were finally conferred their degrees.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Beginning in 1921, women were awarded diplomas that conferred the title associated with the Bachelor of Arts degree.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] But since women were not yet admitted to the Bachelor of Arts degree program, they were excluded from the university's governance structure.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Since University of Cambridge students must belong to a college, and since established colleges remained closed to women, women found admissions restricted to the few university colleges that had been established only for them.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Darwin College, the first graduate college of the university, matriculated both male and female students from its inception in 1964 and elected a mixed fellowship.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Undergraduate colleges, starting with Churchill, Clare, and King's colleges, began admitting women between 1972 and 1988.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Among women's colleges at the university, Girton began admitting male students in 1979, and Lucy Cavendish began admitting men in 2021.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] But the other female-only colleges have remained female-only colleges as of 2023.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] As a result of St Hilda's College, Oxford, ending its ban on male students in 2008, Cambridge is now the only remaining university in the United Kingdom with female-only colleges; Newnham and Murray Edwards only admit female students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] As of the 2019–2020 academic year, the university's male to female enrolment, including post-graduates, was nearly balanced with its total student population being 53% male and 47% female.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In 2018 and later years, the university has come under some criticism and faced legal challenges over alleged sexual harassment at the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In 2019, for example, former student Danielle Bradford, represented by sexual harassment lawyer Ann Olivarius, sued the university for its handling of her sexual misconduct complaint.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] "I was told that I should think about it very carefully because making a complaint could affect my place in my department", Bradford alleged in 2019.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In 2020, hundreds of current and former students accused the university in a letter, citing "a complete failure" to deal with sexual misconduct complaints.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The relationship between the university and the city of Cambridge has sometimes been uneasy.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The phrase town and gown continues to be employed to distinguish between Cambridge residents (town) and University of Cambridge students (gown), who historically wore academical dress.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Ferocious rivalry between Cambridge's residents and university students has periodically erupted over the centuries.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] During the Peasants' Revolt of 1381, strong clashes led to attacks and looting of university properties as locals contested the privileges granted by the British government to the University of Cambridge's academic staff.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Residents burned university property in Market Square to the famed rallying cry "Away with the learning of clerks, away with it!".
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Following these events, the University of Cambridge's Chancellor was given special powers allowing him to prosecute criminals and reestablish order in the city.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Attempts at reconciliation between the city's residents and students followed; in the 16th century, agreements were signed to improve the quality of streets and student accommodation around the city.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] However, this was followed by new confrontations when the plague reached Cambridge in 1630 and colleges refused to assist those affected by the disease by locking their sites.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Such conflicts between Cambridge's residents and university students have largely disappeared since the 16th century, and the university has grown as a source of enormous employment and expanded wealth in Cambridge and the region.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university also has proven a source of extraordinary growth in high tech and biotech start-ups and established companies and associated providers of services to these companies.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Partly because of the University of Cambridge's extensive history, which now exceeds 800 years, the university has developed a large number of traditions, myths, and legends.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Some are true, some are not, and some were true but have been discontinued, or have still been propagated nonetheless by generations of students and tour guides.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] One such discontinued tradition is that of the wooden spoon, the prize awarded to the student with the lowest passing honours grade in the final examinations of the university's Mathematical Tripos.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The last of these spoons was awarded in 1909 to Cuthbert Lempriere Holthouse, an oarsman of the Lady Margaret Boat Club at St John's College.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] It was more than one metre in length and had an oar blade for a handle.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] It can now be seen outside the Senior Combination Room of St John's College.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Since 1908, examination results have been published alphabetically within class rather than in strict order of merit, which made it difficult to ascertain the student with the lowest passing grade deserving of the spoon, leading to discontinuation of the tradition.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Each Christmas Eve, The Festival of Nine Lessons and Carols, sung by the Choir of King's College, are broadcast globally on BBC World Service television and radio and syndicated to hundreds of additional radio stations in the U.S. and elsewhere.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The radio broadcast has been a national Christmas Eve tradition since 1928, though the festival has existed since 1918 and the celebration itself originated even earlier at Truro Cathedral in Cornwall in 1880.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The first television broadcast of the festival was in 1954.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university occupies a central location within the city of Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] University of Cambridge students represent approximately 20 percent of the town's population, which was 145,674 as of 2021, resulting in a lower age demographic in the city.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Most of the university's older colleges are located near the city centre, through which River Cam flows.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Students and others traditionally punt on the River Cam, which provides views of the university's buildings that surround the river.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] A few of the notable University of Cambridge buildings are King's College Chapel; the history faculty building designed by James Stirling; and the New Court and Cripps Buildings at St John's College.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The brickwork of several colleges is notable: Queens' College has some of the earliest patterned brickwork in England and the brick walls of St John's College are examples of English bond, Flemish bond, and Running bond.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university's School of Clinical Medicine is based in Addenbrooke's Hospital, where medical students undergo their three-year clinical placement period after obtaining their BA degree.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The West Cambridge site is undergoing a major expansion and will host new buildings and fields for university sports.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Since 1990, Cambridge Judge Business School, on Trumpington Street, provides management education courses and is consistently ranked among the top 20 business schools in the world by *Financial Times*.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Many of the sites are quite close together, and the area around Cambridge is reasonably flat.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Furthermore, students are not permitted to hold car park permits except under special circumstances.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] For these reasons, the favourite mode of transport for students is the bicycle; an estimated one-fifth of journeys in the city are made by bike.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Cambridge is a collegiate university, which means that its colleges are self-governing and independent, each with its own property, endowments, and income.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Most colleges bring together academics and students from a broad range of disciplines.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Each faculty, school, or department at the university includes academics affiliated with differing colleges.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university is legally structured as an exempt charity and a common law corporation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Its corporate titles include the Chancellor, Masters, and Scholars of the University of Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The college faculties are responsible for giving lectures, arranging seminars, performing research, and determining the syllabi for teaching, all of which is overseen by the university's general board.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Together with the central administration headed by the Vice-Chancellor, the college faculties make up the University of Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Facilities such as libraries are provided on all these levels by the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The Cambridge University Library is the university's largest and primary library.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Squire Law Library is the primary library for the university's students of law.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Individual colleges each maintain a multi-discipline library designed for each college's respective undergraduates.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] College libraries tend to operate 24/7 and their usage in generally restricted to members of the college.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Conversely, libraries operated by departments are generally open to all students of the university, regardless of subject.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The colleges are self-governing institutions with their own endowments and property, each founded as components of the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] All students and most academics are attached to a college.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The colleges' importance lies in the housing, welfare, social functions, and undergraduate teaching they provide.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Each college appoints its own teaching staff and fellows, both of whom are members of a university department.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The colleges also decide which undergraduates to admit to the university, in accordance with university standards and regulations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Costs to students for room and board vary considerably from college to college.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Similarly, the investment in student education by each college at the university varies widely between the colleges.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Cambridge has 31 colleges, two of which, Murray Edwards and Newnham, only admit women.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Darwin was the first college to admit both men and women.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In 1972, Churchill, Clare, and King's were the first previously all-male colleges to admit female undergraduates.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In 1988, Magdalene became the last all-male college to accept women.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Clare Hall and Darwin only admit postgraduates, and Hughes Hall, St Edmund's, and Wolfson only admit mature undergraduate and graduate students who are 21 years old or older on the date of their matriculation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Lucy Cavendish, which was previously a women-only mature college, began admitting both men and women in 2021.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] All other colleges admit both undergraduate and postgraduate students without any age restrictions.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Colleges are not required to admit students in all subjects; some colleges choose not to offer subjects such as architecture, art history, or theology, but most offer a complete range of academic specialties and related courses.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Some colleges maintain a relative strength and associated reputation for expertise in certain academic disciplines.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Churchill, for example, has a reputation for its expertise and focus on sciences and engineering, in part due to the requirement imposed by Winston Churchill upon the college's founding that 70% of its students studied mathematics, engineering, and the sciences.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Other colleges have more informal academic focus and even demonstrate ideological focus, such as King's, which is known for its left-wing political orientation, and Churchill and Robinson, both of which have a reputation for academic focus on sustainability and environmentalism.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Three theological colleges at the university, Westcott House, Westminster College, and Ridley Hall, are members of the Cambridge Theological Federation and associated in partnership with the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In addition to the 31 colleges, the university maintains more than 150 departments, faculties, schools, syndicates, and other academic institutions.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Members of these are usually members of one of the colleges, and responsibility for the entire academic programme of the university is divided among them.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university has a department dedicated to providing continuing education, the Institute of Continuing Education, which is based primarily in Madingley Hall, a 16th-century manor house in Cambridgeshire.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Its award-bearing programmes include both undergraduate certificates and part-time master's degrees.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] A school in the University of Cambridge is a broad administrative grouping of related faculties and other units.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Each has an elected supervisory body known as a Council, composed of representatives of the various constituent bodies.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Teaching and research at the university is organised by faculties.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The faculties have varying organisational substructures that partly reflect their respective histories and the university's operational needs, which may include a number of departments and other institutions.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] A small number of bodies called syndicates hold responsibility for teaching and research, including for the University of Cambridge Local Examinations Syndicate, the University Press, and the University Library.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The chancellor of the university is a ten-year position that is mainly ceremonial and is held currently by Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury, who succeeded David Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Turville in 2025.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The current vice-chancellor is Deborah Prentice, who began her role in July 2023.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] While the chancellor's office is ceremonial, the vice-chancellor serves as the university's *de facto* principal administrative officer.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university's internal governance is carried out almost entirely by Regent House, augmented by some external representation from the audit committee and four external members of the university's council.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university senate consists of all holders of the MA or higher degrees and is responsible for electing the chancellor and the high steward.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Until 1950, when the Cambridge University constituency was abolished, it was also responsible for electing two members of the House of Commons.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Prior to 1926, the university senate was the university's governing body, fulfilling the functions that Regent House has provided since.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Regent House is the university's governing body, comprising all resident senior members of the university and the colleges, the chancellor, the high steward, the deputy high steward, and the commissary.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Public representatives of Regent House are the two proctors, elected to serve for one year terms upon their nominations by the colleges.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Although Cambridge University Council is the university's principal executive and policy-making body, the council reports to, and is held accountable by, Regent House through a variety of checks and balances.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The council is obliged to advise Regent House on matters of general concern to the university, which it does by publishing notices to the *Cambridge University Reporter*, the university's official journal.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In March 2008, Regent House voted to increase from two to four the number of external members on the council, and this was approved by Her Majesty the Queen in July 2008.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The general board of the faculties is responsible for the university's academic and educational policies and is accountable to the council for its management of these affairs.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Faculty boards are accountable to the general board; other boards and syndicates are accountable either to the general board or to the council.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Under this organisational structure, the university's various arms are kept under supervision of both the central administration and Regent House.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The Cambridge University Endowment Fund is the main vehicle of investment for the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In the fiscal year ending 31 July 2025, the university group, excluding colleges, reported a total endowment of £2.76 billion.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In the fiscal year ending 31 July 2025, the central university, excluding colleges, reported total group income of £2.66 billion, of which £605 million was from research grants and contracts.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In July 2022, the *Dear World, Yours Cambridge* Campaign for the university and colleges concluded, raising a total of £2.217 billion in commitments.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The university maintains multiple scholarship programs.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The Stormzy Scholarship for Black UK Students covers tuition costs for two students and maintenance grants for up to four years.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In 2000, Bill Gates of Microsoft donated US$210 million through the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation to endow Gates Cambridge Scholarships for students from outside the United Kingdom to pursue full-time postgraduate study at Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] In October 2021, the university suspended its £400m collaboration with the United Arab Emirates, citing allegations that UAE was involved in illegal hacking of the university's computer and storage systems using NSO Group's Pegasus software.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] UAE also was behind the leak of more than 50,000 phone numbers, including hundreds belonging to British citizens.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] Stephen Toope, the university's outgoing Vice-Chancellor, said the decision to suspend its collaboration with UAE also was a result of additional revelations about UAE's Pegasus software hacking.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] The University of Cambridge borrowed £350 million in October 2012 by issuing 40-year security bonds, whose interest rate is approximately 0.6 percent higher than the British government's 40-year bond.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p01] It is also closely linked to the high tech business cluster known as Silicon Fen and is part of Cambridge University Health Partners, Europe's largest academic health science centre.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Admission to the University of Cambridge is extremely competitive.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] In 2022, for instance, around 15% of applicants were admitted.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] In 2021, Cambridge introduced an over-subscription clause to its offers of admission, which also permits the university to withdraw acceptances if too many students meet its selective entrance criteria.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The clause can be invoked in the event of circumstances outside the reasonable control of the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The clause was introduced following a record number of A-level pupils who obtained the highest grades from teacher assessment, which was introduced due to the cancellation of A-level examinations during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university's standard offer for most courses is set at A*AA, with A*A*A for science courses, or equivalent in other examination systems, e.g.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Based on 2022/23 HESA entry standards data published in domestic league tables, which include a broad range of qualifications beyond the top three exam grades, the average student at the University of Cambridge achieved 206 points.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Due to a high proportion of applicants receiving the highest school grades, an interview process was introduced as a component of consideration for admission.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Interviews are performed by College Fellows, who evaluate candidates on unexamined factors including potential for original thinking and creativity.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Prior to 2020 these interviews were normally held in person but moved online during the COVID-19 pandemic and have, at most colleges, remained online since.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] For exceptional candidates, a matriculation offer is sometimes offered, requiring only two A-levels at grade E or above.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Sutton Trust maintains that the University of Oxford and the University of Cambridge recruit disproportionately from eight schools, which account for 1,310 Oxbridge places over three years contrasted with 1,220 from 2,900 other schools.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Undergraduate applications are processed through UCAS, and the deadline for their submission currently is mid-October in the year before prior to beginning.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Until the 1980s, candidates for all subjects were required to take special entrance examinations, which have since been replaced by additional tests for some subjects, such as the Thinking Skills Assessment and Cambridge Law Test.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university has at times considered reintroducing an admissions exam for all subjects.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Graduate admission is first decided by the faculty or department responsible for the applicant's respective academic subject.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] An offer of acceptance effectively guarantees admission to the university, though not necessarily the applicant's preferred choice of college.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The **Winter Pool** or **inter-College Pool** is part of the undergraduate application process intended to ensure that the best applicants are offered admission.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Approximately 20–25% of undergraduate admissions are awarded through the Pool.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Each college can place applicants in the Winter Pool.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] These applicants' applications are then considered by Admissions Tutors or Directors of Studies during the pool, which takes place over three days in January prior to the release of the university's admissions decisions.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] For each subject, colleges create an ordered list of the pooled applicants they seek to admit, and take turns choosing applicants.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Colleges with specific student requirements, such as mature colleges and women-only colleges, are given priority over applicants eligible for their colleges.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Some applicants are selected from the pool by the college that originally pooled them.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Once all the colleges have selected as many applicants as they need, the pool ends.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Some applicants are then interviewed a second time by the colleges before final admissions decisions are made.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Colleges can pool any candidate, either because the college has no space but believes the applicant is strong enough to get a place, or because the college wants to compare that applicant to other pooled applicants.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Most applicants in the pool are pooled at their original college's discretion, but some candidates meet the compulsory pooling criteria.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] There were, as of the 2020–21 admissions cycle, only two grounds for compulsory pooling.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] For post-qualified applicants, their achieved grades at A level or equivalent and, for applicants with overseas interviews, an interview score of at least eight is achieved in all interviews.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The second criterion does not apply to medicine applicants.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Previously, AS-Level UMS have been used as pooling criteria, but after A-levels became linear this was discontinued.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] As of 2012, there is only one specifically identified category for pooled applicants, which is known as **S**, meaning that the application is in special need of reassessment.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Pooled applicants who are fished by a college may be offered a place immediately or may be invited for an interview.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] In 2020, just 89 applicants were invited for second interviews, 34 of whom received offers of admission.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Each year, approximately 3,500 applicants receive offers from their preference college and a further 1,000 to 1,100 applicants are offered admission by another college through the pool.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] On average, one in five applicants is pooled and around one in four pooled applicants receives an offer of admission.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Statistics released by the university show that some colleges regularly receive particularly high numbers of applicants, and these colleges tend to take fewer applicants from the pool.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Other colleges regularly draw a greater proportion of their undergraduate intake from the pool.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Public debate in the United Kingdom exists over whether admissions processes used at the University of Oxford and Cambridge are entirely merit-based and fair, whether enough students from state schools are encouraged to apply, and whether these students are offered sufficient admission.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] In 2020–21, 71% of all successful applicants were from state schools compared to approximately 93% of all students in the UK who attended state schools and 82% of post-16 students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Others counter that government pressure to increase state school admissions constitutes inappropriate social engineering.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The proportion of undergraduates drawn from independent schools has dropped over the years, constituting, as of 2020, 26% of total admissions among the university's 3,436 applicants from independent schools compared to 23% of the 9,237 applications from state schools.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Cambridge, together with Oxford and Durham, was among those universities that adopted formulae in 2009 to rate the GCSE performance of schools, using data from the Department for Children, Schools and Families, and took this into account when assessing university applicants.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] With the release of admissions figures, *The Guardian* reported in 2013 that ethnic minority candidates had lower success rates in individual subjects even when they had the same grades as white applicants.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university was criticised for what was seen as institutional discrimination against ethnic minority applicants in favour of white applicants.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university denied the claims of institutional discrimination, stating the figures did not take into account other variables.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] A subsequent article reported that, in the years 2010 to 2012, ethnic minority applicants to medicine with 3 A* grades or higher were 20% less likely to gain admission than white applicants with similar grades.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university refused to provide figures for a wider range of subjects, claiming that assembling and releasing such information was excessively costly.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Given the competitive nature of gaining admission to the University of Cambridge, a number of educational consultancies have emerged to offer support with the application process.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Some claim they can improve chances for admission, though these claims have never been independently verified.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] None of these companies are affiliated with or endorsed by the University of Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university informs applicants that all necessary information regarding the application process is publicly available through the university and none of these services is providing any insight not already publicly available to applicants.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The University of Cambridge has been criticised for admitting a lower percentage of black students, though many apply.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Of the 31 colleges at Cambridge, six of them admitted fewer than 10 Black or mixed race students between 2012 and 2016.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Similar criticism exists over a relatively lower admission rate for white working class applicants; in 2019, only 2% of admitted students were white working class.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] In January 2021, Cambridge created foundation courses for disadvantaged students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] While the usual entry requirements are A*AA in A-Levels, the one-year foundation course has 50 places for students who achieve BBB.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] If successful on the course, students receive a recognised CertHE qualification and can progress to degrees in the arts, humanities, and social sciences at the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Candidates include those who have been in care, who are estranged from their families, who have missed significant periods of learning because of health issues, those from low-income backgrounds, and those from schools with few students attending universities.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The University of Cambridge academic year is divided into three academic terms determined by the statutes of the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Michaelmas term lasts from October to December; the Lent term last from January to March; and the Easter term last from April to June.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Within these terms, undergraduate teaching takes place during eight-week periods called full terms.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] According to university statutes, it is a requirement during these periods that all students live within three miles of the Church of St Mary the Great, which is known as keeping term.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Students eligible for graduation must fulfil this condition for nine terms (three years) while pursuing a Bachelor of Arts or twelve terms (four years) when pursuing a Master of Science, engineering, or mathematics degree.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] These terms are shorter than those of many other British universities.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The Tripos exam involves a mixture of lectures organised by the university department) and supervised and organised by the colleges.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Science subjects involve laboratory sessions organised by the departments.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The relative importance of these methods of teaching varies according to the needs of the subject.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Supervisions are typically weekly hour-long sessions in which small groups of students, usually between one and three students, who meet with a member of the teaching staff or with a doctoral student.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Students are normally required to complete an assignment in advance of this supervision, which they then discuss with the supervisor during the session.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The assignment is often an essay on a subject assigned by the supervisor, or a problem sheet set by the lecturer.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Depending on the subject and college, students sometimes receive between one and four supervisory sessions each week.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] This pedagogical system is often cited as being unique to Oxford, where supervisions are known as tutorials, and Cambridge and is sometimes credited with the exceptional nature generally associated with the education at these two world-renowned universities.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] A tutor named William Farish developed the concept of grading students' work quantitatively at the University of Cambridge in 1792.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The University of Cambridge has research departments and teaching faculties in nearly every academic discipline, with research and lectures conducted by university departments.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The colleges are charged with giving or arranging most supervisions, student accommodation, and funding most extracurricular activities.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] During the 1990s, the University of Cambridge added a substantial number of new specialist research laboratories on several sites around the city, and major expansion continues.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] From 2000 to 2006, the University of Cambridge maintained a research partnership with MIT in the United States, known as the Cambridge–MIT Institute, which was discontinued after evolving into what is now called the CMI Partnership Programme.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university's governing body, Regent House, manages and votes on graduations.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] A formal meeting of Regent House, known as a congregation, is held for this purpose, which is typically the final act during which all university procedures for undergraduate and graduate students and other degrees are finalised.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] After degrees are approved, candidates for graduation are required to request their respective college presents them during commencement congregation.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Graduates receiving an undergraduate degree wear the academic dress to which they are entitled prior to graduating; for example, most students becoming Bachelor of Arts graduates wear undergraduate gowns and not BA gowns.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The BA gown without the strings is worn if the graduate is 24 years old or younger, and the MA gown without strings is worn if the graduate is 24 years old or older.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Graduates are presented their degrees in Senate House by each respective college in order of foundation or recognition by the university, except for the university's royal colleges.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] During the University of Cambridge's congregation ceremony, graduands are brought forth by the Praelector of their respective college, who takes them by the right hand and presents them to the vice-chancellor to receive the degree they have earned.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The new graduate then rises, bows, and leaves the Senate House through the Doctor's door in Senate House Passage, where they receive their degree certificate.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The University of Cambridge has 116 libraries.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Cambridge University Library, which holds more than eight million volumes, is the central research library.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] It is a legal deposit library, which entitles it to request a free copy of every book published in the UK and Ireland.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] In addition to the University Library and its dependents, almost every faculty or department has a specialised library; for example, the History Faculty's Seeley Historical Library houses in excess of 100,000 books.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Every college also maintains a library, partly for the purpose of undergraduate teaching; older colleges often possess many early books and manuscripts in a separate library.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] For example, Trinity College's Wren Library houses more than 200,000 books printed before 1800 and Corpus Christi College's Parker Library has more than 600 medieval manuscripts, representing one of the largest such collections in the world.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Churchill Archives Centre on the campus of Churchill College houses the official papers of former British prime ministers Winston Churchill and Margaret Thatcher.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university operates eight arts, cultural, and scientific museums, and a botanical garden.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Cambridge University Museum of Zoology also holds specimens collected by Charles Darwin, an 1831 University of Cambridge alumnus.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Cambridge University Botanic Garden, created in 1831, is the university's botanical garden.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university's publishing arm, Cambridge University Press & Assessment, is the oldest printer and publisher in the world and the second largest university press in the world.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] It is also the largest department of the university by financial income, reporting income above £800 million.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university established its Local Examination Syndicate in 1858, now known as Cambridge University Press & Assessment after its merger with Cambridge University Press.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] It is the largest assessment agency in Europe.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Cambridge University Press & Assessment plays a leading role in researching, developing, and delivering assessments around the world.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The University of Cambridge issues a number of prestigious awards and prizes annually to accomplished University of Cambridge faculty and students.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] It also issues some awards to those of varying global academic accomplishment regardless of whether their recipient is affiliated with the University of Cambridge.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Some of these awards and prizes rank among the world's most estimable academic and intellectual accomplishments.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Owing to its age and its social and academic status, the University of Cambridge is considered to be one of Britain's most prestigious or elite universities and to form, along with the University of Oxford, a top two that stand above other UK universities in this regard.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] As of 2025, the University of Cambridge was ranked sixth in the world by *QS Rankings*, the *ARWU* ranked Cambridge fourth in the world, while *Times Higher Education* ranked Cambridge fifth in the world in its 2025 rankings (released in 2024).
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] As of 2025, the University of Cambridge has been ranked as the top public university in the world for twelve years straight by the Center for World University Rankings.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] One privilege of student life at the University of Cambridge is the opportunity to attend formal dinners at a student's respective college, known as Formal Hall that are held regularly during academic terms and daily at some of the university's colleges.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] During Formal Hall, students typically sit down for a meal in their gowns while fellows and sometimes guests eat separately at a so-called High Table.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The beginning and end of the function is usually marked with grace, which is said in Latin.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Special Formal Halls are organised for Christmas and the Commemoration of Benefactors.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] After the exam period, May Week is held during which it is customary to celebrate by attending May Balls, which are all-night lavish parties held in the colleges where food, drinks, and entertainment are provided.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] So-called Suicide Sunday, the first day of May Week, is a popular date for garden parties.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] In addition to university-wide representation, students can participate in their own college student unions, which are known as Junior Combination Room (JCR) for undergraduates and Middle Combination Room (MCR) for post-graduates.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] These serve as a link between college staff and members and include officers elected annually between the fellow students; individual JCR and MCRs also report to Cambridge Students' Union, which offers training courses for some of the positions within the body.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Numerous student-run societies exist at the University of Cambridge designed to encourage students who share common passions or interests to periodically meet or discuss these interests.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] As of 2010, there were 751 registered societies at the university.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] In addition to these, individual colleges often promote their own societies and sports teams.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Although technically independent from the university, Cambridge Union, a globally renowned debate organisation and the oldest debate organisation in the world, offers students high-level debate and public speaking experience.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Drama societies include the Cambridge University Amateur Dramatic Club (CUADC) and the comedy club Footlights, whose alumni include many well-known show business personalities.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The university's Chamber Orchestra, composed entirely of university students, offers a range of orchestra programs, including symphonies.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Rowing is one of the most popular sports at the University of Cambridge, and there are competitions between colleges, notably the bumps races.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] The University of Cambridge's rowing competition against Oxford is known as the Boat Race.
[src:university-of-cambridge/university-of-cambridge-p02] Varsity matches against Oxford also exist in other sports, including cricket, rugby, chess, and tiddlywinks.
